# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: robert-gordon-university
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The **2010 United Kingdom student protests** were a series of demonstrations in November and December 2010 that took place in several areas of the country, with the focal point of protests being in central London.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Largely student-led, the protests were held in opposition to planned spending cuts to further education and an increase of the cap on tuition fees by the Conservative–Liberal Democrat coalition government following their review into higher education funding in England.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Student groups said that the intended cuts to education were excessive, would damage higher education, give students higher debts, and broke campaign promises made by politicians.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The first major demonstration occurred on 10 November, jointly organised by the National Union of Students (NUS) and the University and College Union (UCU).
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] It involved between 30,000 and 50,000 demonstrators marching through central London, with several hundred branching off to attack and occupy the Conservative Party headquarters.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] This measure brought condemnation from the establishment and a divide within the student movement over the appropriateness of such tactics.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The National Campaign Against Fees and Cuts (NCAFC) called for a mass walk-out and demonstration on 24 November, with occupations taking place at campuses throughout the UK.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A march in central London was kettled in Whitehall, resulting in violent confrontation with protesters.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Further demonstrations were held in central London on 30 November, when police clashed with protesters and kettled them in Trafalgar Square, while other protests took place throughout the country.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Another central London protest took place on 9 December, the day that the proposed reforms were passed into law, with protesters clashing with police and being kettled in Parliament Square.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The student protests were unsuccessful in their aim of preventing the government's reforms in England.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] However, in Wales and Northern Ireland, devolved authorities decided not to increase the fees, which led to differing fee levels for the devolved nations.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The demonstrations were highly controversial in the UK, being condemned for instances of violence and vandalism by both the establishment and by protestors.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The behaviour of the Metropolitan Police in dealing with the protests was also widely criticised for alleged instances of untruthfulness and excessive use of force.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In November 2009, the Labour Party government of Prime Minister Gordon Brown commissioned a study into higher education funding in England.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Chaired by Lord Browne of Madingley, the former chief executive of BP, the report was to be titled the Browne Review.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In the build up to the 2010 general election, the leader of the Liberal Democrats, Nick Clegg, pledged that he would vote against any proposed increase in tuition fees if elected to Parliament.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Following the election and resulting hung parliament, Clegg made an agreement with the Conservative Party to form a coalition government in which Conservative leader David Cameron became Prime Minister and Clegg became Deputy Prime Minister.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The Browne Review was subsequently published in October 2010, and contained the suggestion that the government should remove outright the existing cap of £3,290 on tuition fees.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The government rejected this proposal, instead choosing to keep a cap but increasing it to £9,000.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] David Willetts, the Minister of State for Universities and Science, stated that the measures were "a very progressive package" and "at the end of this we will have a better university system than we have at the moment".
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Contravening his pre-election pledge, Clegg expressed support for the rise in the cap on tuition fees, which would result in future students paying higher fees for their university education.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Student union leaders were critical of the cuts.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The National Union of Students (NUS) feared that the increased cap on tuition fees would prevent potential students from poorer backgrounds from attending university.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Many protesters focused in particular on Clegg's campaign promise that he would oppose any rise in tuition fees.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Two weeks before, on 28 October, a protest was held in the University of Oxford to coincide with a visit from the Liberal Democrat minister and Business Secretary Vince Cable.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Cable cancelled his visit after taking advice from the police about the protest.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Several days later, on 3 November, there was a student protest in Dublin.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The subsequent London protest was described by one Irish reporter as "scenes bizarrely similar" to those in the Irish capital.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The initial event was the largest student protest in Britain since the Labour government first proposed the Teaching and Higher Education Act in 1998.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The first major demonstration in protest at the government's proposed reforms was held on 10 November 2010 in central London, jointly organised by the National Union of Students (NUS) and the University and College Union (UCU).
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] This demonstration was officially known as "Fund Our Future: Stop Education Cuts", although also termed "Demo 2010" or "Demo-lition 10.11.10".
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Arriving from all regions of Great Britain and Northern Ireland, approximately 30,000 to 52,000 protesters attended the demonstration.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Political groups that sent contingents to take part included the Labour Party, Plaid Cymru, the Green Party, Socialist Workers Party, Socialist Party, Revolution, Young Communist League, Revolutionary Communist Group, and Communist Students.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A few members of parliament (MPs) joined the demonstration, among them Labour MP John McDonnell, who told reporters: "This is the biggest workers' and students' demonstration in decades.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] It just shows what can be done when people get angry.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Representatives of the National Pensioners Convention also took part, with the group's banner carrier, Janet Shapiro, stating that: "We're here because we believe education should be free, funded by the taxpayer.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Hunt stated that making the public university system in Britain "the most expensive in the world" was unfair, that discouraging young people from going to college was not progressive, and that the increase in tuition fees represented further debts for students.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The rally was also addressed by NUS President Aaron Porter and the Trades Union Congress Deputy general secretary Frances O'Grady.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] O'Grady offered the message to the government that: "Don't you dare tell us we're all in this together.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The deficit certainly wasn't caused by the students." The protest was scheduled to end at 2 pm, but slightly overran.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The Metropolitan Police were expecting 20,000 demonstrators to turn out, well below the 50,000 figure most widely quoted in the press after the event, and did not expect any violence, so deployed only 225 officers to police the event.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In the afternoon, as protesters passed the Houses of Parliament and moved towards Tate Britain for the rally, several thousand surrounded 30 Millbank in Westminster, campaign headquarters of the Conservative Party, despite attempts by NUS organisers to stop them.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Forcing their way past the limited police presence, approximately 200 people broke in and occupied the building, whilst a thousand more cheered and supported them from outside.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] These protesters lit placards on fire, and smashed windows before occupying and vandalising the reception area.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Staff working in the building were evacuated by police around 1 pm.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Around 100 protesters proceeded to the roof of the building, chanting slogans including "Greece!
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Initial press sources blamed this action on a group of anarchists.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] This was later disputed, with a reporter from *The Guardian* noting that most of the protesters occupying the building were students who had been radicalised in opposition to the cuts, and were not all political anarchists.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Riot police from the Territorial Support Group arrived an hour after the building was occupied to remove the protesters.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In retaliation, the police were pelted with eggs, rotten fruit, banners, and shards of glass.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] One of the protesters on the building's roof, Edward Woolard, threw a fire extinguisher onto the police below.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] He received instant criticism from some of the protesting crowds, who called on those on the roof to "stop throwing shit".
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] To control the situation, police used the controversial technique of kettling to trap the protesters within Millbank Square, the forecourt to 30 Millbank, whilst protesters on the outside of the building were pushed back.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The police began letting demonstrators out of the building from 6:30 pm, arresting those whom they believed were responsible for vandalism.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In all, 14 people were injured and required hospitalisation, at least three of whom were police officers, whilst police arrested 35 of the demonstrators, sending them off to various police stations around the city.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Later accounts that the numbers arrested had risen to 54, (33 men and 21 women), ten of whom were aged under 18 and the majority of whom were students.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The actions of a minority, out of 50,000 people, is regrettable." Oxford University's Student Union (OUSU) President David Barclay issued a statement declaring that "OUSU supports the rights of students to protest non-violently.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Contrastingly, other student leaders, trade unionists, and academics expressed support for elements of the occupation of 30 Millbank.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Meanwhile, various university Conservative societies around London condemned the protests, and criticised students' unions for providing the "false impression that the majority of students are left-wing" and opposed to the governments' proposed reforms.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The Metropolitan Police Service admitted that they were unprepared to deal with the occupation of 30 Millbank, something which they had not been expecting.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Sir Paul Stephenson, the Metropolitan Police's Commissioner, told the press that he was "embarrassed" by how police had lost control of the situation, and condemned what he saw as "thuggish, loutish behaviour by criminals".
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Stephenson remarked that "the one thing I would say is that it must have been an awful time for the people trying to go about their daily business in those buildings.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] I feel terribly sorry that they have had to go through what must have been quite a traumatic experience...
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] We are determined to make sure that sort of thing does not happen again on our streets.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] I'm clear on that, the Met is clear on that." His views were echoed by Mayor of London Boris Johnson, who stated: "This is intolerable and all those involved will be pursued and they will face the full force of the law...
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The Metropolitan Police commissioner has assured me that there will be a vigorous post-incident investigation.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Prime Minister David Cameron condemned the occupation of Millbank, stating that he would not abandon his position on the issue of education cuts.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Speaking from the 2010 G20 Seoul summit in South Korea, Cameron said the occasion had been "extremely serious" and praised the "bravery" of the police officers.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] He also stated that the actions of the protesters were "unacceptable" and that "I was worried for the safety of the people in the building because I know people who work there".
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The following morning, Clegg went on ITV's *Daybreak* to state: "I should have been more careful perhaps in signing that pledge [to not increase tuition fees]...
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At the time [prior to his election] I really thought we could do it.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The *Financial Times* reported that an anonymous vice-chancellor from a London university had told them that the violence would undermine the campaign, and that it "could not have gone better for the government.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In the following days, smaller protests were held in Manchester and Cambridge, with no violent confrontations.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] On 11 November, student protesters occupied a building at the University of Manchester for three hours, demanding to see the accounts that discussed how government funding cuts would affect students.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Between 60 and 100 students held a peaceful sit-in at Manchester's John Owens Building on Oxford Road after an NUS meeting earlier that day.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Representing this group, protester Jeremy Buck said: "This is just what a few students who had the energy left after the London demo managed to achieve...
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Imagine what will happen when they have enough time to organise properly for the 24th.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] It is a matter of watch this space." That same day, protesters at the University of Cambridge held a demonstration against the cuts at the university's annual science, engineering and technology careers fair.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] On 23 November, anti-education cuts protesters had assembled outside of the offices of *The Guardian* newspaper, where Clegg was giving his Hugo Young lecture.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] They brought out an effigy of Clegg, sentencing it to death and executing it by hanging, shouting the slogan "Nick Clegg, shame on you, shame on you for turning blue".
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A second significant demonstration took place in London on 24 November, which again led to clashes with police, this time outside Whitehall, after police kettled a large crowd.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] An organisation known as the National Campaign Against Fees and Cuts (NCAFC) organised a mass national walk-out of education and protest for 24 November.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] As a part of this, demonstrations were held in London and other locations across the United Kingdom.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The NCAFC encouraged protesters to use social media to invite others to join them.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Several thousand protesters, most of whom were students or school children, gathered in Trafalgar Square, central London, late in the morning.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] They proceeded toward Whitehall shouting the slogan, "fuck David Cameron".
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Believing that there had been a lack of officers at 10 November demonstration, the Metropolitan Police drafted in 1000 police officers from across Greater London to oversee the event, almost five times the number at 10 November.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Police informed press that they planned to monitor fringe elements within the demonstration whom they believed planned to encourage "vandalism and violence".
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At Whitehall, just before 1 pm, police prevented the protesters from reaching Parliament Square and the Houses of Parliament, setting up a line of riot police to kettle the protesters.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A reporter *The Guardian* described the crowd at this point as being "predominantly good natured, although very noisy".
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Nonetheless, the demonstrators tried to push through the police line, leading to clashes.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] An unoccupied police van which had been left in the midst of the crowd was vandalised; protesters rocked it back and forth, climbed on its roof, smashed its windows, wrote graffiti on it and threw a smoke bomb inside.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A group of school girls encircled the van, urging people not to vandalise it.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At around 6 pm, mounted police charged at the north end of the crowd to push them back; despite video evidence police denied that this was an actual charge, describing it as crowd control using horses.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Various bus shelters and ticket machines in the area were vandalised, with Transport for London diverting buses away from the unrest.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Approximately 200 protesters were unable to escape and remained kettled in Whitehall.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Police falsely informed press that the crowd were provided with toilet facilities and water; protesters disputed these claims on social media, with ULU President Clare Solomon commenting on Facebook: "we're still illegally kettled in the freezing cold on Whitehall.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] No food, water or toilets despite what the police are telling the media.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Thousands of young people needing to go home." To keep warm, protesters set fire to a ticket machine within the Square, prompting riot police to secure the machine and put out the flames.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] From 9 to 10 pm, police permitted the rest of the Whitehall protesters to leave, approximately nine to ten hours after they had first been contained, some being searched as they left.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] During the clashes, police arrested 41 protesters.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Across the UK, protesters occupied university buildings in at least 12 universities.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] On 23 November, protesters occupied the picture gallery corridor of Royal Holloway, University of London.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] They were later joined by supportive members of university staff who took part in what was labelled a "teach-in".
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] On 24 November, the Language Centre at London South Bank University was occupied for 51 hours by over 100 students as part of the "Defend LSBU!
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] They're quoting Harry Potter rather than Che Guevara." Protesters also occupied the University of East London, demanding that university managers "put pressure on the government on the issue of H[higher] E[ducation] cuts and tuition fee rises".
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A group of about 100 occupied a lecture theatre in the Roscoe Building.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At the University of Oxford, students initially occupied the Radcliffe Camera.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At the University of Cambridge, 200 students scaled the fence of Senate House and marched onto the grounds of King's College, then on 26 November students started an 11-day occupation of part of Old Schools, the main administrative block of the university.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At the University of Bristol, 2000 protesters clashed with police when they tried to move into the city centre.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In Brighton, 3000 demonstrators marched through the city, with nearly 50 occupying a university building.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Hundreds of students from Kingston University and various local schools staged an impromptu march through the town and a sit down protest at College Roundabout, leading to one arrest.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Hundreds of them had walked out of the local Allerton Grange High School to join the demonstration, and later occupied the Michael Sadler lecture theatre and a room at Leeds Metropolitan University.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A room at the University of Plymouth was also occupied.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At Cardiff University, around 200 protesters occupied a lecture theatre after failing to gain entry to the vice-chancellor's building.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] During the Whitehall incident, the Metropolitan Police publicly defended their use of kettling, with Chief Inspector Jane Connors claiming that they had only used it as "a last resort".
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At a meeting of the Metropolitan Police Authority the following day, the Metropolitan Police's Commissioner Sir Paul Stephenson defended the tactics.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] He was criticised by Jenny Jones, a Green Party member of the London Assembly, who told him: "when you imprison thousands of people, which is essentially what you did yesterday, you do have a duty of care to them...
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] You kept people for nine-and-a-half hours.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A spokesperson for Prime Minister Cameron stated that "people have a right to engage in lawful and peaceful protest, but there is no place for violence or intimidation", while education minister David Willetts responded by claiming that protesting students did not understand the government's plans.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Clegg stated on BBC Radio 2 that "I hate in politics, as in life, to make promises that you then find you can't keep.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] We made a promise we can't deliver – we didn't win the election outright and there are compromises in coalition." Labour Party leader Ed Miliband stated that he would not rule out joining further demonstrations, remarking that "I was quite tempted to go out and talk to them [the protesters].
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Peaceful demonstrations are part of our society.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A third central London protest was organised for Tuesday 30 November, a day that saw cold temperatures and snow in the city.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Protesters assembled at Trafalgar Square, but a police line prevented their march down Whitehall towards the Houses of Parliament; the NCAFC accused the Police of "pre-emptively block[ing]" the protest route.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Fearing that they would be kettled in the Square, protesters dispersed throughout the city center, pursued by police.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Other officers stood photographing and filming the students for later identification, while police vans blocked off certain streets.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Some protesters chanted "Peaceful protest!
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Peaceful protest!" and "no ifs, no buts, no education cuts", and others blew vuvuzelas and played reggae from portable stereo systems.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A BBC reporter talked to members of the demonstration, noting that while many desired a peaceful outcome, others believed that violent confrontation with the police was inevitable.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Many were angry with how they had been portrayed in the media, with one commenting that confrontation was not caused by "hardcore anarchists" but by "students who are very, very angry".
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Many protesters ran onto Pall Mall and then past St James's Park.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Denied access to Parliament Square by police, they turned around and headed toward Westminster Abbey.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A reporter from *The Guardian* noted that "the march is fracturing – people are going up different streets and getting lost.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The police kettled those in the Square, whilst some of the protesters waved banners with slogans such as "Don't put the kettle on, Mr.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Cameron" and "I Can't Believe It's Not Thatcher".
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The police "put lines [of officers] across all the exits" to the kettled area of the Square, but reportedly allowed small groups of protesters to leave, even though the majority, around 150 to 200, decided to stay and continue protesting in the snow.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Some protesters burned placards and one spray-painted the word "Revolution" on Nelson's Column.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Others threw plastic bottles and fireworks at police lines, and at one point there "was a scuffle as a knot of policemen rushed one of the protesters, grabbing him to arrest him, and the crowd flocked angrily to the area".
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At another time, a group of riot police moved into the crowd of protesters to attempt to secure Nelson's Column, only to be surrounded by demonstrators shouting "Who's kettling who?
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] We're kettling you!" Other slogans shouted at police during the protest included "Shame on you!" and "Your job's next".
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Police then arrested 146 demonstrators who refused to leave the Square; 139 of them were arrested for breach of the peace, whilst seven were arrested on suspicion of violent disorder.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Seven more had been arrested in central London earlier in the day.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The night before, on 28 November, a crowd of two to three hundred protesters gathered outside of Lewisham Town Hall in Catford, south London, where a council meeting was then in progress, to protest against wider public sector cuts.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Several Youtube videos of the incident were shown on national news, including the BBC.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Many of the protesters had come from nearby sixth forms (due to potential Education Maintenance Allowance cuts) and also from Goldsmiths College.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Demonstrators, playing music and political slogans from boomboxes forced their way into the building, where a smoke bomb was let off, while another protester climbed onto the roof and unfurled a banner.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Several more flares were set off outside and windows smashed, with riot police from the Territorial Support Group close by, were called and several arrests were made.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] One of the protesters, Sue Luxton, a former Green Party councillor who had subsequently become a teacher, told the press that "I wanted to peacefully express my anger at the cuts...
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] On the day of the main demonstration, there were also further protests across the United Kingdom, including in Cardiff, Cambridge, Colchester, Newcastle, Bath, Leeds, Sheffield, Edinburgh, Liverpool, Belfast, Brighton, York, Manchester, Plymouth, Scunthorpe and Bristol.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] About 1,500 students, including school children, took part in the protest in Brighton, whilst protests in Bristol involved police being pelted with mustard and ten demonstrators were arrested.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In Sheffield, police were pelted with snowballs as they guarded the constituency office of Nick Clegg from a crowd of two hundred protesters.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The British protests coincided with those in Italy, where demonstrations occurred in Milan, Turin, Naples, Venice, Palermo, Bari, Genoa, and Rome where riot police were called in to prevent students from gaining access to the parliament building.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Meanwhile, whilst occupations that had begun the previous week continued at University College London, Newcastle University and the University of Cambridge, a new one began at the University of Nottingham, where 150 protesters occupied a building.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] University buildings and local government buildings were occupied in Birmingham and Oxford while police blocked an attempt at occupation of the council building in York.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The protesters occupying the council chamber in Birmingham left after four hours, with a police spokesperson commending the protesters for their "wholly peaceful" behaviour, and noting that it "couldn't have been more different from the violent clashes seen recently in London".
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] ULU members handed out green hard hats with the words "Tax the banks, not the students" on them, whilst a rally was held in Bloomsbury at midday, where ULU President Solomon addressed the crowd.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The Metropolitan Police had positioned lines of riot police and police vans along the Houses of Parliament, to prevent any protesters gaining access to it.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Superintendent Julia Pendry issued a statement saying: "Protesters will be allowed sight and sound of parliament.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] However, there is evidence to suggest a number of people will come to London intent on causing violence and disorder.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The protesters marched from Bloomsbury to Parliament Square in the afternoon, where they pushed down metal barriers and occupied the Square.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Around 3:30 pm, police kettled those several thousand protesters in the square, preventing them from leaving, stating that it was necessary "due to the level of violence that our officers are facing".
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Mounted police charged into the crowd on one side of the Square in an attempt to disperse them.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A field hospital was set up on the green providing emergency first aid to protesters as well as tea and food within the containment area.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Around 30 protesters were treated, most for head injuries.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Police used batons to hit protesters, and a St John Ambulance member told press that he had treated ten protesters for head injuries from being struck by police batons by 4.30 pm.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] One protester, philosophy student Alfie Meadows, suffered a blow to the head from a police truncheon that knocked him unconscious.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Taken to hospital, it was discovered that he was suffering from bleeding of the brain, and required brain surgery.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Reporter Jonathan Haynes of *The Guardian*, who was present, characterised the police tactics as "very heavy handed".
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Police informed press that they were allowing young and vulnerable protesters to leave the kettle, but those inside the kettle, including journalists, asserted that this was untrue.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At 5:41 pm, news reached the protesters that the government had voted to support the proposals.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Clashes ensued between the crowd and the police, and the protesters pulled along metal fencing to separate themselves from riot police, who were trying to push them all into the centre of the Square.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Later on in the evening, with the protesters still kettled in the Square, protesters smashed all of the windows on the ground floor of Her Majesty's Treasury.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] At 21:15, the protest was forced onto Westminster Bridge where it was kettled until approximately 23:30.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Due to the Parliament Square protest being kettled, many other demonstrators could not enter the Square and so disseminated across much of the rest of central London.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Meanwhile, many of those students who remained around the area of Trafalgar Square continued to protest, with about 150 holding a sit-in in the adjacent National Gallery, while others attempted to set fire to the Trafalgar Square Christmas tree.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] During the protests, a car taking The Prince of Wales and The Duchess of Cornwall to the evening's Royal Variety Performance at the London Palladium was attacked on Regent Street and Home Secretary Theresa May confirmed a protester 'made contact' with Camilla.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In Oxford Street, Topshop was damaged, as rioters sprayed "pay your tax" on the building and broke windows.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Home Secretary Theresa May issued a statement in which she "utterly condemned" the actions of the protesters, and declared that "What we are seeing in London tonight, the wanton vandalism, smashing of windows, has nothing to do with peaceful protest...
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Nearly 50 people complained to the Independent Police Complaints Commission (IPCC) about police behaviour during the various protests held around the country, with the majority directed against the Metropolitan Police, including complaints of violence used against protesters.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Following the protests, video footage posted on YouTube showed Jody McIntyre, a protester with cerebral palsy, involved in an altercation with police.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The footage showed McIntyre, who had positioned himself in the front line facing police, being pulled out of his wheelchair and dragged across the ground by Metropolitan Police officers.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] While McIntyre later said he had been pulled out of the wheelchair twice, only one incident is shown in the video.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] On 13 December, he was interviewed about the incident by BBC journalist Ben Brown, an interview later described by *The Guardian* newspaper as "having a distinct lack of sympathy from the BBC" and it was noted that the incident had "attracted thousands of complaints".
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] McIntyre's complaint was later rejected by Scotland Yard.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] His subsequent appeal was partly upheld by the IPCC.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Street medics treated student protesters during the parliament square protest on Thursday 9 December, the day of the scheduled vote to raise university tuition fees.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] A field tent was set up on the green providing emergency first aid to protesters as well as tea and food within the containment area.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Alfie Meadows was acquitted of all charges in 2013.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In September 2023 the Metropolitan Police apologised to him and agreed a financial settlement.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] On 30 November, following the third main day of protesting, the Welsh Assembly announced that it would not permit an increase in fees for Welsh students.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In July 2011, three school children will challenge the kettling of children at the 24 November 2010 protest.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In September 2011, students in Northern Ireland succeeded in getting the Northern Ireland Assembly to freeze tuition fees, avoiding the large fee increases in England.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Student leaders in Northern Ireland cited the wider protests across the UK as one reason for their success.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] As of 2020, this has saved Northern Ireland university students £1 billion in tuition fees compared to English students.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In November 2012, two years after the 2010 demonstrations, protests ignited again from the student movement.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Organised by the NUS, around 10,000 demonstrators marched in central London.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] Cooper complained that the allegations were untrue, threatened his future academic prospects and left his reputation "as badly trashed" as the Millbank Tower.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The years following the student protests saw a leftward shift in the politics of the NUS.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] In 2014 the NUS Conference voted in support of free education, reversing the union's previous policy of advocating a graduate tax as a replacement for tuition fees, which it had adopted in the late 2000s.
[src:robert-gordon-university/2010-united-kingdom-student-protests] The Student Broad Left made progressive gains in the mid-2010s, culminating in the election of SBL candidate Malia Bouattia as NUS President.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-art-gallery] Following a competition, the winning design by Alexander Marshall Mackenzie and James Matthews began construction in 1883 and was opened in 7 July 1885.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-art-gallery] There were further additions, again by Mackenzie, in 1901 and 1905, including the addition of a sculpture court.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-art-gallery] In April 2020, the gallery made 50 artworks available digitally via the Smartify app.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-art-gallery] In October 2020, Aberdeen Art Gallery was named one of the five winners of the 2020 ArtFund Museum of the Year Award.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-art-gallery] ArtFund increased the prize money to £200,000 and changed the format of the award to five winners in response to the challenges faced by the museum sector during the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-art-gallery] The Fine Arts collection of the Aberdeen Art Gallery has grown steadily since its foundation in 1885, highlighted with works by such artists as Monet and Renoir as well as more modern artists like John Bulloch Souter, Ian Hamilton Finlay, and James McBey.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-art-gallery] The permanent collection includes 18th-century works by Henry Raeburn, William Hogarth, Allan Ramsay and Joshua Reynolds, and 20th-century works by Paul Nash and Francis Bacon, the Post-Impressionists and the Scottish Colourists, as well as applied arts and crafts.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-art-gallery] The central hall is supported by granite columns in a variety of colours, derived from different quarries in the local area and far beyond.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-art-gallery] At the western end of the building, with a room inside and a monument outside, is a major war memorial.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-art-gallery] The war memorial was built in the 1920s as a part of the rapid expansion of the Aberdeen Art Gallery and was funded by a public subscription.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-art-gallery] The Memorial Court court has a display of several books of remembrance and rolls of honour, commemorating the fallen of World War I, World War II, the Merchant Navy and Fishing Fleets in World War II, and from conflicts after 1945.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-art-gallery] Another addition to the Gallery during this time of rapid expansion was Cowdray Hall.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-art-gallery] Cowdray Hall is a concert venue for music and performances and was opened by King George V and Queen Mary on 25 September 1925.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-art-gallery] The Gallery was closed for a programme of renovations commencing in 2015.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-art-gallery] The £34.6 million redevelopment was designed by Hoskins Architects and carried out by the contractors McLaughlin & Harvey.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-art-gallery] The project won an award from the Scottish Civic Trust for making an outstanding contribution to the quality and appearance of the built environment, as well as the trust's National Panel Special Award.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] The council has been under no overall control since 2002.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] Since 2022 it has been led by a Scottish National Party and Liberal Democrat coalition.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] It meets at Aberdeen Town House and has its main offices at the neighbouring Marischal College.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen was made a royal burgh by David I (reigned 1124–1153).
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] The burgh of Aberdeen was governed by a corporation, also known as the town council.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] Elections for the council were only introduced in 1833.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] Prior to that the council was not an elected body; when vacancies arose the existing council appointed successors.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] As Aberdeen grew, the council's powers were inadequate to cater for the needs of the growing urban area.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] A separate police commission was established in 1795 with powers to levy taxes and provide infrastructure ('police' in this context being its older meaning of civic government rather than law enforcement).
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] The first police commission was short-lived, but it was resurrected in 1818 after the town council went bankrupt in 1817.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] From 1818 until 1871 there was a dual system of local government, with the town council and police commission having different roles in Aberdeen's administration.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] The police commission was eventually abolished in 1871 and its functions absorbed by the town council.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen was historically part of Aberdeenshire, but the functions affecting the burgh which operated at county level were relatively few, largely being limited to judicial functions and lieutenancy.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] When elected county councils were created in 1890 under the Local Government (Scotland) Act 1889, Aberdeen Corporation was deemed capable of running county-level local government functions, and so the burgh was excluded from the area administered by Aberdeenshire County Council.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] In 1891 Aberdeen's boundaries were significantly enlarged, absorbing the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside, plus the Torry area on the south bank of the River Dee.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] The act of parliament which expanded the burgh also confirmed that Aberdeen was entitled to be called a city; it had commonly been described as a city prior to that, but (like most Scottish cities) without official recognition.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] The historic county boundary between Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire in this area followed the River Dee.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] Following the absorption of Torry on the south bank of the river in 1891, the city straddled the two counties.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen was made a county of itself in 1899, removing the city from the two counties for lieutenancy and other purposes as well as local government functions.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] The city boundaries were subsequently enlarged several times, gaining further territory from both Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire, notably in 1935, 1952 and 1970.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] Local government across Scotland was reorganised in 1975 under the Local Government (Scotland) Act 1973, which replaced the counties, burghs and landward districts with a two-tier system of regions and districts.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] One of the districts was called 'City of Aberdeen', which formed part of Grampian Region.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] City of Aberdeen District Council was therefore a lower-tier district authority, with upper-tier regional functions being provided by Grampian Regional Council.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] The City of Aberdeen district covered a larger area than the pre-1975 city, taking in the parishes of Dyce, Newhills, Old Machar, and Peterculter from Aberdeenshire and Nigg from Kincardineshire.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] All except Dyce had previously ceded territory to the city in pre-1975 boundary changes.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] The parish of Nigg added in 1975 just covered the residual rural parts of the old parish around Cove Bay; Nigg village itself had been absorbed into the city in 1935.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] The parish of Old Machar was named after St Machar's Cathedral in Old Aberdeen, which had been absorbed into the city in 1891; the parish of Old Machar that was absorbed in 1975 was just the residual part of the cathedral's old parish which lay north of the River Don, including Bridge of Don.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] Local government was reorganised again in 1996 under the Local Government etc.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] (Scotland) Act 1994, which abolished the regions and districts created in 1975 and established 32 single-tier council areas across Scotland.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] The existing City of Aberdeen District became one of the new council areas.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] The 1994 Act named the new council area 'City of Aberdeen', but this was changed to 'Aberdeen City' by a council resolution on 9 May 1995, before the new council area came into force, allowing the new council to take the name 'Aberdeen City Council'.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] Following the 2022 election a Scottish National Party and Liberal Democrats coalition took control of the council.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] The first election to the City of Aberdeen District Council was held in 1974, initially operating as a shadow authority alongside the outgoing authorities until the new system came into force on 16 May 1975.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] A shadow authority was again elected in 1995 ahead of the change to council areas which came into force on 1 April 1996.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] The role of Lord Provost of Aberdeen is largely ceremonial.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] They chair full council meetings and act as the council's civic figurehead.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] Political leadership is provided by the leader of the council.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen City Council currently comprises 45 councillors, who represent the city's wards, and is headed by the Lord Provost.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] Prior to the 2012 council election there were 43 members of Aberdeen City Council.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] Between 2003 and 2007, the council was under the control of a Liberal Democrat and Conservative coalition, holding 23 of the 43 seats on the council.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] Prior to the 2003 election, the council had been considered a Labour stronghold.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] Two Liberal Democrat councillors became independents during this period due to personal controversies, while the four strong Conservative group split in August 2010, with two councillors forming the Scottish Conservative Group and two others the Aberdeen Conservative Group.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] After the May 2012 election, the control of the council shifted back to the Labour Party, supported in a coalition by three Conservative and three Independent councillors, giving the administration 23 seats.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] The Labour/Conservative/Independent coalition continued after the 2017 election, but with a change in the balance of power within the coalition.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] Labour were reduced to nine councillors (subsequently suspended from membership by the Scottish Labour Party for forming a coalition with the Conservatives), whilst the Conservatives had eleven councillors elected.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] These Conservative and suspended "Aberdeen Labour" councillors were joined in coalition by three Independent councillors, one of who had left the Liberal Democrats just days after the council election.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] In December 2019 a councillor elected as a Conservative became an Independent following his conviction for sexual assault.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] This led to the ruling coalition becoming a minority administration comprising only 22 of the 45 councillors.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] Between 2017 and 2021 the council had Co-Leaders Douglas Lumsden (Conservative) and Jenny Laing (“Aberdeen Labour”) as a result of the coalition agreement.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] Following Douglas Lumsden's election to the Scottish Parliament in May 2021 Jenny Laing became sole Leader of the council.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] After the 2022 election the SNP and Liberal Democrats agreed to form a partnership to lead the Council for the next five years.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] At the Council's statutory meeting on 18 May 2022, SNP councillor David Cameron was elected Lord Provost and Liberal Democrat Councillor Steve Delaney was elected Depute Provost.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] SNP Group Leader Alex Nicoll and Liberal Democrat Group Leader Ian Yuill became Co-Leaders of the Council.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] Effective April 2, 2026, Desmond Buchanan, Councillor for George Street/Harbour ward resigned.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] The Returning Officer announced the By-Election will take place on Thursday, June 25th 2026.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] Council meetings are held at Aberdeen Town House on Broad Street, which was built in 1874 and substantially extended in 1975, including a new council chamber.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] The council's main offices are now in the neighbouring Marischal College.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] The council moved into the renovated former college building in 2011.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] Before May 2007, councillors represented 43 single-member wards election on a first-past-the-post basis.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] On 3 May 2007, the single transferable vote system was used for the first time and multi-member wards were introduced, each ward electing three or four councillors.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] The Local Government Boundary Commission for Scotland completed its final recommendations for new wards for all the council areas of Scotland.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] Aberdeen is divided into 13 multi-member wards, electing a total of 45 councillors.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-city-council] This system was introduced as a result of the Local Governance (Scotland) Act 2004, and is designed to produce a form of proportional representation.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen received royal burgh status from David I of Scotland (1124–1153), which transformed the city economically.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The traditional industries of fishing, paper-making, shipbuilding, and textiles have been overtaken by the oil industry and Aberdeen's seaport.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Heliport is one of the busiest commercial heliports in the world, and the seaport is the largest in the north-east part of Scotland.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] A university town, the city is known for the University of Aberdeen, founded in 1495 as King's College, the fifth oldest university in the English-speaking world and located in Old Aberdeen.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] During the mid-18th to mid-20th centuries, Aberdeen's buildings incorporated locally quarried grey granite, which may sparkle like silver because of its high mica content.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Since the discovery of North Sea oil in 1969, Aberdeen has been known as the offshore **oil capital of Europe**.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Based upon the discovery of prehistoric villages around the mouths of the rivers Dee and Don, the area around Aberdeen is thought to have been settled for at least 6,000 years.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The name given to Aberdeen translates as 'mouth of the river Don', and is recorded as Aberdon in 1172 and Aberden in c.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The first element of the name is the Pictish word *aber* 'river mouth'.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The second element is from the Celtic river goddess Devona.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is usually described as within the historical Pictish territory and became Gaelic-speaking at some time in the medieval period.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Old Aberdeen is the approximate location of Aberdon, the first settlement of Aberdeen; this literally means "the mouth of the Don".
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The Celtic word *aber* means "river mouth", as in modern Welsh (Aberystwyth, Aberdare, Aberbeeg etc.).
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Gaelic name is *Obar Dheathain* (variation: *Obairreadhain*; **obar* presumably being a loan from the earlier Pictish; the Gaelic term is *inbhir*), and in Latin, the Romans referred to the river as *Devana*.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Medieval (or Ecclesiastical) Latin has it as *Aberdonia*.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The local Doric pronunciation, [ˌeːbərˈdin] ⓘ or [ˈeːbərdin] ⓘ (with a long *ay* sound), is frequently rendered *Aiberdeen* or *Aiberdein*.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen area has seen human settlement for at least 8,000 years.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The city began as two separate burghs: Old Aberdeen at the mouth of the river Don; and New Aberdeen, a fishing and trading settlement, where the Denburn waterway entered the river Dee estuary.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The earliest charter was granted by William the Lion in 1179 and confirmed the corporate rights granted by David I.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] In 1214, Aberdeen Burgesses were granted a Royal Charter by Alexander II of Scotland giving them the sole right to form a Guild.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] This body exercised power in the composition of the local council, and the affairs of the town.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The Burgesses of the Guild were an integral part of the council for more than 700 years and played a considerable role in the growth and development of Aberdeen.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] In 1319, the Great Charter of Robert the Bruce transformed Aberdeen into a property-owning and financially independent community.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Granted with it was the nearby Forest of Stocket, whose income formed the basis for the city's Common Good Fund which still benefits Aberdonians.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of Scottish Independence, Aberdeen was under English rule, so Robert the Bruce laid siege to Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308, followed by executing the English garrison.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The city was burned by Edward III of England in 1336, but was rebuilt and extended.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The city was strongly fortified to prevent attacks by neighbouring lords, but the gates were removed by 1770.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's medieval council registers survive from 1398 onwards and are exceptional for their quantity and continuity among surviving Scottish burgh records.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The earliest eight volumes, from 1398 to 1511, have been included in the UNESCO UK Memory of the World Register, and have been edited in a digital edition.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of the Three Kingdoms of 1644 to 1647 the city was plundered by both sides.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] In 1644, it was taken and ransacked by Royalist troops after the Battle of Aberdeen and two years later it was stormed by a Royalist force under the command of the George Gordon, 2nd Marquess of Huntly.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] An outbreak of bubonic plague over 1687 and 1688 killed 8.5% of the population, adding to the economic and demographic damage caused by war.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] In the 18th century, a new Town Hall was built and the first social services appeared with the Aberdeen Infirmary at Woolmanhill in 1739 and the Aberdeen Lunatic Asylum in 1800.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The expensive infrastructure works led to the city becoming bankrupt in 1817 during the Post-Napoleonic depression, an economic downturn immediately after the Napoleonic Wars; but the city's prosperity later recovered.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The increasing economic importance of Aberdeen and the development of the shipbuilding and fishing industries led to the construction of the present harbour including Victoria Dock and the South Breakwater, and the extension of the North Pier.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Gas street lighting arrived in 1824 and an enhanced water supply appeared in 1830 when water was pumped from the Dee to a reservoir in Union Place.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] An underground sewer system replaced open sewers in 1865.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The city absorbed the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee in 1891.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Over the course of World War II Aberdeen was attacked 32 times by the German Luftwaffe.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] One of the most devastating attacks was on Wednesday 21 April 1943 when 29 Luftwaffe Dornier 217s flying from Stavanger, Norway attacked the city between the hours of 22:17 and 23:04.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] A total of 98 civilians and 27 servicemen were killed, along with 12,000 houses damaged, after a mixture of 127 Incendiary, High Explosive and Cluster bombs were dropped on the city in one night.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Two books written in 2018 and 2022 using bombing records held in London identified that unexploded bombs from the 1943 raid were found in the 1950s and 1980s making the bombs dropped 129 in total.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Damage from the raid can still be seen in some parts of Aberdeen.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The arms and banner of the city show three silver towers on red.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] This motif dates from at least the time of Robert the Bruce and represents the buildings that stood on the three hills of medieval Aberdeen: Aberdeen Castle on Castle Hill (today's Castlegate); the city gate on Port Hill; and a church on St Catherine's Hill (now levelled).
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] "Bon Accord" is the motto of the city and is French for "Good Agreement".
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Legend tells that its use dates from a password used by Robert the Bruce during the 14th century Wars of Scottish Independence, when he and his men laid siege to the English-held Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] It is still widely present in the city, throughout street names, business names and the city's Bon Accord shopping mall.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The shield in the coat of arms is supported by two leopards.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] A local magazine is called the "Leopard" and, when Union Bridge was widened in the 20th century, small statues of the creature in a sitting position were cast and placed on top of the railing posts (known locally as Kelly's Cats).
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The city's toast is "Happy to meet, sorry to part, happy to meet again".
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] In 2012, HSBC named Aberdeen as a leading business hub and one of eight 'super cities' spearheading the UK's economy, marking it as the only city in Scotland so designated.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] In 2018, Aberdeen was found to be the best city in the UK to start a business in a study released by card payment firm Paymentsense.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen City is one of 32 council areas of Scotland, administered by Aberdeen City Council.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The council meets at Aberdeen Town House and has its main offices in the adjoining Marischal College.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The civic head and chair of the council is the Lord Provost.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The council area is also divided into 30 community council areas, 29 of which had community councils operating as at August 2024.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The first burgh of Aberdeen, covering just the New Aberdeen area near the mouth of the Dee, was created by David I (reigned 1124–1153).
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Neighbouring Old Aberdeen to the north was subsequently made a separate burgh in 1489.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] In 1891 the city boundaries were significantly enlarged, absorbing the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside, plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Following the absorption of Torry in 1891, the city boundaries straddled the counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was made a county of itself in 1899.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] In 1975 the burgh was replaced by the larger City of Aberdeen district within the Grampian region.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Further local government reforms in 1996 replaced the districts and regions created in 1975 with council areas; the pre-1996 City of Aberdeen district became the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] In the Scottish Parliament, the city is represented by three constituencies with different boundaries: Aberdeen Central and Aberdeen Donside are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Deeside and North Kincardine includes the North Kincardine ward of Aberdeenshire Council.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] A further seven MSPs are elected as part of the North East Scotland electoral region.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] In the European Parliament the city was represented by six MEPs as part of the all-inclusive Scotland constituency.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is represented in the Parliament of the United Kingdom by two constituencies, Aberdeen North and Aberdeen South, which are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Being situated between two river mouths, the city has little natural exposure of bedrock.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The small amount of geophysics done, and occasional building-related exposures, combined with small exposures in the banks of the River Don, suggest that it is actually sited on an inlier of Devonian "Old Red" sandstones and silts.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The city extends to 186 km2 (72 sq mi), and includes the former burghs of Old Aberdeen, New Aberdeen, Woodside and the Torry area to the south of River Dee.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] In 2024, this gave the city a population density of 1,249 inhabitants per square kilometre (3,230/sq mi).
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The city is built on many hills, with the original beginnings of the city growing from Castle Hill, St.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] When compared to mainland Europe, Aberdeen is further north than almost all of Denmark and plenty of southern Sweden, being just south of Gothenburg in terms of latitude.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen features an oceanic climate (Köppen *Cfb*), with far milder winter temperatures than one might expect for its northern location.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] However, statistically speaking, it is still the coldest city in the UK.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] During the winter, especially throughout December, the length of the day is very short, averaging 6 hours and 41 minutes between sunrise and sunset at the winter solstice.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] As winter progresses, the length of the day grows fairly quickly, to 8 hours and 20 minutes by the end of January.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Around summer solstice, the days will be around 18 hours long, having 17 hours and 55 minutes between sunrise and sunset.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] During this time of the year marginal nautical twilight lasts the entire night.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Temperatures at this time of year hover around 17.0 °C (62.6 °F) during the day in most of the urban area, though nearer 16.0 °C (60.8 °F) directly on the coast, and around 18.0 to 19.0 °C (64.4 to 66.2 °F) in the westernmost suburbs.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Two weather stations collect climate data for the area, Aberdeen/Dyce Airport, and Craibstone.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Both are about 4+1⁄2 miles (7 km) to the northwest of the city centre, and given that they are in close proximity to each other, exhibit very similar climatic regimes.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Dyce tends to have marginally warmer daytime temperatures year-round owing to its slightly lower elevation, though it is more susceptible to harsh frosts.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The coldest temperature to occur in recent years was −16.8 °C (1.8 °F) during December 2010, while the following winter, Dyce set a new February high-temperature station record on 28 February 2012 of 17.2 °C (63.0 °F), and a new March high temperature record of 21.6 °C (70.9 °F) on 25 March 2012.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The average temperature of the sea ranges from 6.6 °C (43.9 °F) in March to 13.8 °C (56.8 °F) in August.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen locality population estimate is 198,590 (2020).
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] For the wider settlement of Aberdeen including Cove Bay and Dyce, the population estimate is 220,690 (2020).
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] For Aberdeen City council area, the population estimate is 231,780 (2024).
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] In 1396, the population was about 3,000.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The 2011 census showed fewer young people in Aberdeen, with 16.4% under 16, as opposed to the national average of 19.2%.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] According to the 2011 census Aberdeen is 91.9% white, ethnically, 24.7% were born outside Scotland, higher than the national average of 16%.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Of this population, 7.6% were born in other parts of the UK.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] 8.2% of Aberdonians stated to be from an ethnic minority (non-white) in the 2011 census, with 9,519 (4.3%) being Asian, with 3,385 (1.5%) coming from India and 2,187 (1.0%) being Chinese.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The city has around 5,610 (2.6%) residents of African or Caribbean origin, which is a higher percentage than both Glasgow and Edinburgh.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] In the household, there were 97,013 individual dwellings recorded in the city, of which 61% were privately owned, 9% privately rented and 23% rented from the council.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The most popular type of dwellings are apartments which comprise 49% of residences followed by semi-detached at just below 22%.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The median income of a household in the city is £16,813 (the mean income is £20,292) (2005) which places approximately 18% households in the city below the poverty line (defined as 60% of the mean income).
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Conversely, an Aberdeen postcode has the second highest number of millionaires of any postcode in the UK.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The proportion of people residing in Aberdeen born outside the UK was 21.1% in 2022, compared with 15.9% in 2011 and 6.3% in 2001.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Below are the fifteen largest overseas-born groups in Aberdeen according to the 2022 census, alongside the two previous censuses.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Christianity is the main religion practised in the city.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's largest denominations are the Church of Scotland (through the Presbytery of Aberdeen) and the Roman Catholic Church, both with numerous churches across the city, with the Scottish Episcopal Church having the third-largest number.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The census in 2022 showed that Aberdeen has the highest proportion of non-religious residents of any city in Scotland, with 58% of citizens claiming to have no religion.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] In the Middle Ages, the Kirk of St Nicholas was the only burgh kirk and one of Scotland's largest parish churches.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Like a number of other Scottish kirks, it was subdivided after the Reformation, in this case into the East and West churches.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] At that time, the city also was home to houses of the Carmelites (Whitefriars) and Franciscans (Greyfriars).
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The latter survives in modified form as the chapel of Marischal College.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] St Machar's Cathedral was built twenty years after David I (1124–1153) transferred the pre-Reformation diocese from Mortlach in Banffshire to Old Aberdeen in 1137.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Except the episcopate of William Elphinstone (1484–1511), building progressed slowly.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Gavin Dunbar, who followed him in 1518, completed the structure by adding the two western spires and the southern transept.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] It is now a congregation of the Church of Scotland.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Mary's Cathedral is a Roman Catholic cathedral in Gothic style, erected in 1859.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Andrew's Cathedral serves the Scottish Episcopal Church.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] It was constructed in 1817 as Archibald Simpson's first commission and contains a memorial to the consecration of the first bishop of the Episcopal Church in the United States of America, which took place nearby.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] In 1804, St Peter's Church, the first permanent Roman Catholic church in the city after the Reformation was built.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Numerous other Protestant denominations have a presence in Aberdeen.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The Salvation Army citadel on the Castlegate dominates the view of the east end of Union Street.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there is a Unitarian church, established in 1833 and located in Skene Terrace.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Christadelphians have been present in Aberdeen since at least 1844.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Over the years, they have rented space to meet at a number of locations and currently meet in the Inchgarth Community Centre in Garthdee.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Quaker meetinghouse on Crown Street, the only purpose built Friends meeting house in Scotland that is still in use today.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there are a number of Baptist congregations in the city, and Evangelical congregations have been appearing in significant numbers since the late 2000s.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The city also has two meeting houses of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church).
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] There are also four mosques in Aberdeen which serve the Islamic community in the city.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] There is an Orthodox Jewish Synagogue established in 1945.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Thai Buddhist temple located in the Hazelhead area of the city.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] There are no formal Hindu buildings, although there is a fortnightly Hindu religious gathering on the first and third Sunday afternoons at Queens Cross Parish church hall.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen has a small Baháʼí society.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,756 residents aged three and over, 76,650 (35.2%) considered themselves able to speak or read the Scots language.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,760 residents aged three and over, 2,919 (1.3%) considered themselves able to speak or read Gaelic.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Traditionally, Aberdeen was home to fishing, textile mills, shipbuilding and paper-making.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] These industries have been largely replaced.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] High technology developments in the electronics design and development industry, research in agriculture and fishing and the oil industry, which have been largely responsible for Aberdeen's economic growth, are now major parts of Aberdeen's economy.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Until the 1970s, most of Aberdeen's leading industries dated from the 18th century; mainly these were textiles, foundry work, shipbuilding and paper-making, the oldest industry in the city, with paper having been first made there in 1694.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Paper-making has reduced in importance since the closures of Donside Paper Mill in 2001 and the Davidson Mill in 2005 leaving the Stoneywood Paper Mill with a workforce of approximately 500.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Textile production ended in 2004 when Richards of Aberdeen closed.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Grey granite was quarried at Rubislaw quarry for more than 300 years, and used for paving setts, kerb and building stones, and monumental and other ornamental pieces.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen granite was used to build the terraces of the Houses of Parliament and Waterloo Bridge in London.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The current owners have begun pumping 40 years of rainwater from the quarry to develop a heritage centre on the site.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] In-shore fishing was once the predominant industry but was surpassed by deep-sea fisheries, which derived a great impetus from improved technologies throughout the 20th century.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Catches have fallen because of overfishing and the use of the harbour by oil support vessels, and so although still an important fishing port it is now eclipsed by the more northerly ports of Peterhead and Fraserburgh.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The Fisheries Research Services are headquartered in Aberdeen, and there is a marine research laboratory there.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is well regarded for the agricultural and soil research carried out at The James Hutton Institute (formerly the Macaulay Land Use Research Institute), which has close links to the city's two universities.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The Rowett Research Institute is a world-renowned research centre for studies into food and nutrition located in Aberdeen.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] It has produced three Nobel laureates and there is a high concentration of life scientists working in the city.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] As oil reserves in the North Sea decrease, there is an effort to rebrand Aberdeen as the **energy capital of Europe** rather than the oil capital, and there is interest in the development of new energy sources, and technology transfer from oil into renewable energy and other industries is underway.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The "Energetica" initiative led by Scottish Enterprise has been designed to accelerate this process.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has become a major world centre for undersea petroleum technology.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen had been a major maritime centre throughout the 19th century, when a group of local entrepreneurs launched the first steam-powered trawler.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The steam trawling industry expanded and by 1933 Aberdeen was Scotland's top fishing port, employing nearly 3,000 men with 300 vessels sailing from its harbour.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] By the time oil was coming on stream, much of the trawling fleet had relocated to Peterhead.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Geologists had speculated about oil and gas in the North Sea since the middle of the 20th century, but tapping its deep and inhospitable waters was another story.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] With the Middle Eastern oil sheiks becoming more aware of the political and economic power of their oil reserves and government threats of rationing, the industry began to consider the North Sea as a viable source of oil.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Exploration commenced in the 1960s and the first major find in the British sector was in November 1970 in the Forties field, 110 miles (180 km) east of Aberdeen.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] By late 1975, after years of intense construction, the necessary infrastructure was in place.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Oil flowed through the Forties pipeline system directly to the refinery at far-away Grangemouth.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] In 2011, the Centre for Cities named Aberdeen as the best-placed city for growth in Britain, as the country looked to emerge from the recent economic downturn.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] With energy still providing the backbone of the local economy, recent years have seen very large new investment in the North Sea owing to rising oil prices and favourable government tax incentives.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] This has led to several oil majors and independents building new global offices in the city.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Five of Scotland's top ten businesses are based in Aberdeen with a collective turnover of £14 billion, yielding a profit in excess of £2.4 billion.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Alongside this 29 of Scotland's top 100 businesses are located in Aberdeen with an employment rate of 77.9%, making it the second highest UK city for employment.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Figures released in 2016 ranked Aberdeen as having the second highest number of patents processed per person in the UK.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The traditional shopping streets are Union Street and George Street, now complemented by shopping centres, including the Bon Accord Centre and the Trinity Shopping Centre.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] A £190 million retail development, Union Square, reached completion in late September/early October 2009.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Major retail parks away from the city centre include the Berryden Retail Park, the Kittybrewster Retail Park and the Beach Boulevard Retail Park.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Market has been rebuilt twice, but closed in 2020.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] In March 2004, Aberdeen was awarded Fairtrade City status by the Fairtrade Foundation.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's architecture is known for its principal use during the Victorian era of granite, which has led to its local nickname of the Granite City.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] In Castle Street, a continuation eastwards of Union Street, is the new Aberdeen Town House, a very prominent landmark in Aberdeen, built between 1868 and 1873 to a design by Peddie and Kinnear.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Alexander Marshall Mackenzie's extension to Marischal College on Broad Street, opened by King Edward VII in 1906, created the second largest granite building in the world (after the Escorial, Madrid).
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has long been famous for its 45 parks and gardens, and citywide floral displays which include two million roses, eleven million daffodils and three million crocuses.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The city has won the Royal Horticultural Society's Britain in Bloom 'Best City' award ten times, the overall Scotland in Bloom competition twenty times and the large city category every year since 1968.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] However, despite recent spurious reports, Aberdeen has never been banned from the Britain in Bloom competition.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The city won the 2006 Scotland in Bloom "Best City" award along with the International Cities in Bloom award.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The suburb of Dyce also won the Small Towns award.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Duthie Park opened in 1883 on the north bank of the River Dee.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] It was named after and given to the city by Miss Elizabeth Crombie Duthie of Ruthrieston in 1881.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Hazlehead Park, is large and forested, and located on the outskirts of the city.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Johnston Gardens is a small park of one hectare in the west end of the city.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] In 2002, the garden was named the best garden in the British Islands.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Seaton Park, formerly the grounds of a private house, is on the edge of the grounds of St Machar's Cathedral and was acquired for the city in 1947.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has hosted several theatres throughout its history, some of which have been converted or destroyed.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Today, all railway services to the south run via Dundee.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The faster main line from Aberdeen to Perth via Forfar and Strathmore closed in 1967, as a result of the Beeching cuts; the faster main line from Perth to Edinburgh via Glenfarg also closed subsequently in 1970.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] A second station, at Dyce, serves the north of the city centre; it is on the Aberdeen–Inverness line.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] First Aberdeen operates the majority of city bus services, as the successor to Grampian Regional Transport (GRT) and Aberdeen Corporation Tramways.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Secondary operators include Stagecoach Bluebird and Stagecoach South Scotland.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is the global headquarters of parent company FirstGroup, having grown from the GRT Group.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] First is still based at the former Aberdeen Tramways depot on King Street, which has now been redeveloped into a new headquarters and bus depot.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] On 18 April 2025, the "Aberdeen Adventurer" tour bus scheme ran by McGill's Bus Services was launched with 10 stops around the city on a 75-minute loop.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Stops include King's College, Pittodrie Stadium and the Aberdeen Art Gallery with the service due to end on 20 September 2026.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen International Airport (ABZ), sited in Dyce in the north of the city, serves domestic and international destinations in France, the Netherlands, Spain, Ireland and Scandinavian countries.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The heliport, which serves the oil industry and rescue services, is one of the world's busiest commercial heliports.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is connected to the UK's National Cycle Network; it has a track to the south, connecting to cities including Dundee and Edinburgh, and one to the north that forks about 10 miles (15 km) from the city into two different tracks heading to Inverness and Fraserburgh respectively.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Two popular shared-use paths, along old railway lines, are the Deeside Way to Banchory (which will eventually connect to Ballater) and the Formartine and Buchan Way to Ellon, both used by a mixture of cyclists, walkers and occasionally horses.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] In May 2026, a self-service e-bike hire scheme was introduced in Aberdeen, operated by Voi Technology.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Some 350 bikes are available on a pay-as-you-go basis.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The scheme replaced an earlier bike hire scheme which was operated between 2022 and 2024 by *The Big Issue* and Sharebike but which was scrapped because of funding issues as well as vandalism.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Harbour is important as the largest in the north of Scotland and serves the ferry route to Orkney and Shetland.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Established in 1136, the harbour has been referred to as the "oldest business in Britain".
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The Dee Estuary, Aberdeen's harbour, started out as a fishing port, moving on to steam trawlers and serving the oil industry; it is now a major port of departure for the Baltic and Scandinavia.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has two universities, the ancient University of Aberdeen, and Robert Gordon University, a modern university often referred to as RGU.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has a high proportion of students of 11.5%, higher than the national average of 7%.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen began as King's College, Aberdeen, which was founded in 1495 by William Elphinstone (1431–1514), Bishop of Aberdeen and Chancellor of Scotland.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Marischal College, a separate institution, was founded in New Aberdeen by George Keith, fifth Earl Marischal of Scotland in 1593.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] These institutions were merged by the Universities (Scotland) Act 1858 to form the University of Aberdeen.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The university is the fifth oldest in the English-speaking world and offers degrees in a full range of disciplines.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Its main campus is in Old Aberdeen in the north of the city and it currently has approximately 14,000 students.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The university's debating society is the oldest in Scotland, founded in 1848 as the King's College Debating Society.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Today, Aberdeen is consistently ranked among the top 200 universities in the world and is ranked within the top 20 universities in the United Kingdom.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was also named the 2019 Scottish University of the Year by The Times and Sunday Times Good University Guide.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] In early 2022, Aberdeen opened the Science Teaching Hub.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Robert Gordon's College (originally Robert Gordon's Hospital) was founded in 1750 by the merchant Robert Gordon, grandson of the map maker Robert Gordon of Straloch, and was further endowed in 1816 by Alexander Simpson of Collyhill.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Originally devoted to the instruction and maintenance of the sons of poor burgesses of guild and trade in the city, it was reorganised in 1881 as a day and night school for secondary and technical education.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] In 1903, the vocational education component of the college was designated a Central Institution and was renamed as the Robert Gordon Institute of Technology in 1965.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] In 1992, university status was awarded and it became Robert Gordon University.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The university has expanded and developed significantly in recent years, and was named Best Modern University in the UK for 2012 by *The Sunday Times*.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] It was previously *The Sunday Times* Scottish University of the Year for 2011, primarily because of its record on graduate employment.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is also home to two artistic schools: Gray's School of Art, founded in 1886, which is one of the oldest established colleges of art in the UK.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Scott Sutherland School of Architecture and Built Environment, was one of the first architectural schools to have its training courses recognised by the Royal Institute of British Architects.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Both are now part of Robert Gordon University and are based at its Garthdee campus.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] North East Scotland College has several campuses in the city and offers a wide variety of part-time and full-time courses leading to several different qualifications in science.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Agricultural College is based just outside Aberdeen, on the Craibstone Estate.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] This is situated beside the roundabout for Aberdeen Airport on the A96.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The college provides three services—Learning, Research and Consultancy.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The college features many land-based courses such as Agriculture, Countryside Management, Sustainable Environmental Management and Rural Business Management.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] There are a variety of courses from diplomas to master's degrees.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The Marine Laboratory Aberdeen, which specialises in fisheries, Macaulay Land Use Research Institute (soil science), and the Rowett Research Institute (animal nutrition) are some other higher education institutions.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen College of Performing Arts also provides full-time Drama and Musical Theatre training at Further Education level.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] There are currently 15 secondary schools and 54 primary schools which are run by the city council.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] There are a number of private schools in Aberdeen: Robert Gordon's College, Albyn School, St Margaret's School for Girls, the International School of Aberdeen and a Waldorf/Steiner School.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] State secondary schools in Aberdeen include Aberdeen Grammar School, Bridge of Don Academy, Bucksburn Academy, Cults Academy, Dyce Academy, Harlaw Academy, Hazlehead Academy, Lochside Academy, Northfield Academy, Oldmachar Academy and St Machar Academy.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p01] Independent primary and secondary schools in Aberdeen include Albyn School, Robert Gordon's College, St Margaret's School for Girls, and the International School of Aberdeen.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The city has a wide range of cultural activities, amenities, and museums, and is regularly visited by Scotland's National Arts Companies.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] It was awarded the Nicholson Trophy for the best-kept town at the Britain in Bloom contest in 1975.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery houses a collection of Impressionist, Victorian, Scottish and 20th-century British paintings as well as collections of silver and glass.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] It also includes The Alexander Macdonald Bequest, a collection of late 19th-century works donated by the museum's first benefactor and a constantly changing collection of contemporary work and regular visiting exhibitions.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery reopened in 2019 after a four-year refurbishment costing £34.6m.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Maritime Museum, located in Shiprow, tells the story of Aberdeen's links with the sea from the days of sail and clipper ships to the latest oil and gas exploration technology.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] It includes an 8.5-metre-high (28 ft) model of the Murchison oil production platform and a 19th-century assembly taken from Rattray Head lighthouse Provost Ross' House is the second oldest dwelling house in the city.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] It was built in 1593 and became the residence of Provost John Ross of Arnage in 1702.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The house retains some original medieval features, including a kitchen, fireplaces and beam-and-board ceilings.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The Gordon Highlanders Museum tells the story of one of Scotland's best known regiments.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Provost Skene's House on Flourmill Lane dates from 1545 and is the oldest surviving townhouse in the city.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] It reopened in October 2021 after significant refurbishment costing £3.8m.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] One of the new exhibitions is a Hall of Heroes featuring 100 Aberdonians who have made a significant contribution to the city.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The Tollbooth Museum on the Castlegate (currently closed to visitors) is a former jail, which first opened as a public museum in 1995.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Treasure Hub is a storage facility for Aberdeen Museums and Galleries containing over 100,000 items.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The store is open for infrequent tours, for example as part of Doors Open Day.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Marischal Museum holds the principal collections of the University of Aberdeen, comprising some 80,000 items in the areas of fine art, Scottish history and archaeology, and European, Mediterranean and Near Eastern archaeology.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The permanent displays and reference collections are augmented by regular temporary exhibitions, and since its closure to the public it now has a virtual online presence It closed to the public in 2008.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The King's Museum acts as the main museum of the university now.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Student Show, performed annually without interruption since 1921, under the auspices of the Aberdeen Students' Charities Campaign, is the longest-running of its kind in the United Kingdom.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] It is written, produced and performed by students and graduates of Aberdeen's universities and higher education institutions.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Since 1929—other than on a handful of occasions—it has been staged at His Majesty's Theatre.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] National festivals which visited Aberdeen in 2012 included the British Science Festival in September, hosted by the University of Aberdeen but with events also taking place at Robert Gordon University and at other venues across the city.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] In February 2012 the University of Aberdeen also hosted the Inter Varsity Folk Dance Festival, the longest-running folk festival in the United Kingdom.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Spectra, an annual light festival hosted in different locations across the city.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Nuart, a festival showcasing street art around the city.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] In 2020, the WayWORD Festival was launched by the University of Aberdeen WORD centre for creative writing.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] This yearly programme celebrates the arts through readings, performances, workshops and discussion panels.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] There have been many notable headliners including Val McDermid, Irvine Welsh and Douglas Stuart (writer).
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Galas are held annually throughout the city, the most notable being the Culter Gala, which is usually held on the last Saturday of May.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The local dialect of Lowland Scots is often known as Doric and is spoken not just in the city, but across the northeast of Scotland.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] It differs somewhat from other Scots dialects: most noticeable are the pronunciation "f" for what is normally written "wh" and "ee" for what in standard English would usually be written "oo" (Scots "ui").
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Every year the annual Doric Festival takes place in Aberdeenshire to celebrate the history of the north-east's language.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Scotland's oldest newspaper the *Press and Journal*, a local and regional newspaper first published in 1747.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The *Press and Journal* and its sister paper the tabloid *Evening Express* are printed six days a week by Aberdeen Journals.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] There was one free newspaper, the *Aberdeen Citizen*.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] BBC Scotland has a network studio production base in the city's Beechgrove area, and BBC Aberdeen produces *The Beechgrove Potting Shed* for radio while Tern Television produces *The Beechgrove Garden*.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The city is also home to STV North (formerly Grampian Television), which produces the regional news programmes such as *STV News at Six*, as well as local commercials.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The station, based at Craigshaw Business Park in Tullos, was based at larger studios in Queens Cross from September 1961 until June 2003.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Music venues include the Music Hall and the P&J Live.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen region has given its name to a number of dishes, including the Aberdeen buttery (also known as "rowie") and Aberdeen Sausage.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] In 2015, a study was published in The Scotsman which analysed the presence of branded fast food outlets in Scotland.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Of the ten towns and cities analysed, Aberdeen was found to have the lowest per capita concentration, with just 0.12 stores per 1,000 inhabitants.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The public health service in Scotland, NHS Scotland provides for the people of Aberdeen through the NHS Grampian health board.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Albyn Hospital is a private hospital located in the west end of the city.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen City Council is responsible for city-owned infrastructure which is paid for by a mixture of Council Tax and income from the Scottish Government.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure and services run by the council include: nursery, primary and secondary education, roads, clearing snow in winter, city wardens, maintaining parks, refuse collection, economic development, public analyst, public mortuary, street cleaning and street lighting.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure in private hands includes electricity, gas and telecoms.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Water and sewerage services are provided by Scottish Water.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The first ever recorded game of football, was outlined by teacher David Wedderburn in his book "Vocabula" written in 1633, during his time teaching at Aberdeen Grammar School.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] There is one Aberdeen-based football club in the SPFL.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] (The Dons) play in the Scottish Premiership at Pittodrie Stadium.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The club won the European Cup Winners Cup and the European Super Cup in 1983, the Scottish Premier League Championship four times (1955, 1980, 1984 and 1985), and the Scottish Cup eight times (1947, 1970, 1982, 1983, 1984, 1986, 1990 and 2025).
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of Alex Ferguson, Aberdeen was a major force in British football during the 1980s.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of McInnes the team won the 2014 Scottish League Cup and followed it up with a second-place league finish for the first time in more than 20 years in the following season.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] But it was over the last few seasons that results stagnated and McInnes was replaced by former Aberdeen and Newcastle player Stephen Glass.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Cove Rangers, as of season 2024-25 play in League One, at the Balmoral Stadium in the suburb of Cove Bay.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Cove won the Highland Football League championship in 2001, 2008, 2009, 2013 and 2019, winning the League Two play-offs in 2019 and earning promotion.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] At the point at which the 2019/20 League Two season was curtailed due to the COVID-19 pandemic, Cove were sitting top of the League Two table and were promoted as Champions.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Other local teams include Banks o'Dee who play at Spain Park in the Highland Football League and members of the SJFA North Region; Culter, Dyce, Stoneywood Parkvale, Glentanar, Sunnybank Hall Russell United, Bridge of Don Thistle and Hermes.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen hosted Caledonia Reds, a Scottish rugby team, before they merged with the Glasgow Warriors in 1998.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] In 2005 the President of the SRU said it was hoped eventually to establish a professional team in Aberdeen.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] In November 2008 the city hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Canada, with Scotland winning 41–0.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] In November 2010 the city once again hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Samoa, with Scotland winning 19–16.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Warriors rugby league team play in the Rugby League Conference Division One.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The Warriors also run Under 15's and 17's teams.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Grammar School won the Saltire Schools Cup in 2011.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The Royal Aberdeen Golf Club, founded in 1780 is the sixth oldest golf club in the world, and hosted the Senior British Open in 2005, and the amateur team event the Walker Cup in 2011.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Royal Aberdeen also hosted the Scottish Open in 2014, won by Justin Rose.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The club has a second course, and there are public golf courses at Auchmill, Balnagask, Hazlehead and King's Links.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] There are new courses planned for the area, including world-class facilities with major financial backing, the city and shire are set to become important in golf tourism.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] In Summer 2012, Donald Trump opened a new state of the art golf course at Menie, just north of the city, as the Trump International Golf Links, Scotland.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Ice hockey in Aberdeen boasts a history that began in the early 20th century.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Glaciarium on Forbesfield Road became a hub for games, featuring teams like the Grammar School Former Pupils and the Aberdeen Ice Hockey Club.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] However, the sport all but died out with the onset of WW1.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The sport was revived in the city with the opening of the Linx Ice Arena in 1992.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Lynx plays in the Scottish National League and is based at the Linx Ice Arena.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Founded in 2005, they won back to back regular season titles in 2022-23 and 2023–24 and won the play-off championship in 2015-16 and again in 2024–25.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] They regularly sell out home games and are the second best supported sports team in the city after Aberdeen FC.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The City of Aberdeen Swim Team (COAST) was based in Northfield swimming pool, but since the opening of the Aberdeen Aquatics Centre in 2014, it is now based there, as it has a 50 m pool as opposed to the 25 m pool at Northfield.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The team comprises several smaller swimming clubs and has enjoyed success throughout Scotland and in international competitions.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Three of the team's swimmers qualified for the 2006 Commonwealth Games.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] There are four boat clubs that row on the River Dee: Aberdeen Boat Club (ABC), Aberdeen Schools Rowing Association (ASRA), Aberdeen University Boat Club (AUBC) and Robert Gordon University Boat Club (RGUBC).
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The city has one national league side, Stoneywood-Dyce.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Local "Grades" cricket has been played in Aberdeen since 1884.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeenshire were the 2009 and 2014 Scottish National Premier League and Scottish Cup Champions.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen University Shinty Club (Scottish Gaelic: Club Camanachd Oilthigh Obar Dheathain) is the oldest constituted shinty club in the world, dating back to 1861.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The city council operates public tennis courts in various parks including an indoor tennis centre at Westburn Park.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The Beach Leisure Centre is home to a climbing wall, gymnasium and a swimming pool.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] There are numerous swimming pools dotted around the city notably the largest, the Bon Accord Baths which closed down in 2008.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] In common with many other major towns and cities in the UK, Aberdeen has an active roller derby league, Granite City Roller Derby.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Roughnecks American football club is a new team that started in 2012 and is the first team that Aberdeen has witnessed since the Granite City Oilers that began in 1986 and were wound up in the mid-1990s.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Oilers Floorball Club was founded in 2007.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The club initially attracted a range of experienced Scandinavian and other European players who were studying in Aberdeen.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Since their formation, Aberdeen Oilers have played in the British Floorball Northern League and went on to win the league in the 2008/09 season.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The club played a major role in setting up a ladies league in Scotland.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The Oilers' ladies team ended up second in the first ladies league season (2008/09).
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] One of the earliest known disasters is the Storegga Slide in the mesolithic period in 6225–6170 BCE which caused tsunami waves to hit North sea coastal areas, with wave heights of 3-6 meters in the north east Scotland areas.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] In 1876, the River Dee ferryboat disaster took place when 32 people drowned in the mouth of the River Dee.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The 20th century includes a World War II disaster when in 1943, a Luftwaffe raid dropped 129 bombs on Aberdeen resulting in 125 deaths..
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] In 1964, a typhoid outbreak occurred with 400 cases and three fatalities.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] In 1983, the Aberdeen taxi driver George Murdoch was killed, the murder case is unsolved.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] In modern time, accidents have been related with offshore drilling.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] In 1988, the oil platform Piper Alpha, located 190 km north-east of Aberdeen, exploded and collapsed, killing 165.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The accident is the worst ever offshore oil and gas disaster in terms of lives lost.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Hazlehead Park contains a memorial to the crew. .
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] In 1995, Bristow Helicopters Flight 56C was struck by lightning and emergency landed in the sea.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] The 18 crew and passengers on board survived.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] In 2009, the Bond Offshore Helicopters Flight 85N crashed 20 km north-east of Peterhead, while returning from an oil platform to Aberdeen Airport.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberdeen-p02] Johnston Gardens contains a memorial to the deceased.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] Abertay launched the world's first computer games degree in 1997 and in 2017 held a programme of events celebrating 20 Years of Games.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] Abertay was also the first to offer a degree in Ethical Hacking, starting in 2006.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] In 1872 Sir David Baxter, 1st Baronet of Kilmaron, died and bequeathed £20,000 (£1.96 million adjusting for inflation) for the establishment of a mechanics' institute in Dundee.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] The Baxter bequest was intended to create an educational establishment permitting young male working mechanics and other craftsmen to better themselves.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] After some years of delay the trustees finalised a scheme and met the conditions of the bequest and the Dundee Technical Institute opened on 15 October 1888 in grounds, purchased from University College, Dundee, adjacent to Small's Wynd, Dundee.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] In 1901 the Dundee Technical Institute enrolled 723 part-time students and was one of the first education hubs to be recognised as a 'central institution' by the Scotch Education Department.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] In 1906 a new site in Bell Street, Dundee was purchased to build a larger complex to accommodate a growing student population.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] In 1911 the completed complex was formally opened as the Dundee Technical College & School of Art.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] In 1909 James Duncan of Jordanstone left £60,000 (£6.17 million adjusting for inflation) to establish an art college in Dundee.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] The college of art became a formally separate institution, known as the Duncan of Jordanstone College of Art and Design, in 1975, remaining independent until 1994 when it became part of the University of Dundee.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] The First World War reduced enrolments and growth but the vocational nature of the institute meant that its classes were relevant to the war effort.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] The first women students enrolled in 1914.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] After the Second World War enrolments and the scope of delivery continued to expand, as did the reputation of the institute.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] By 1951 the institute was teaching courses that led to examinations for the external degrees of the University of London in pharmacy, mechanical, civil, and electrical engineering.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] In 1955 the National Council for Technological Awards was established and validated diplomas in technology which were equivalent in standard if not in name to honours degrees.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] The institution began offering degrees itself in 1956.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] Abertay University was created in 1994, under the Further and Higher Education Act 1992, granting the title "University of Abertay Dundee" to the Dundee Institute of Technology.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] Since 2014 the university has promoted itself as Abertay University.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] The university's name was formally changed to Abertay University by an Order of Council on 1 September 2019.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] Abertay was the first university in the world to offer a "computer games" degree in 1997.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] Abertay was the UK's first university to be recognised as a Centre for Excellence in Computer Games Education, and is associated with a business support programme for computer game startups.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] Abertay University is situated in the centre of Dundee.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] The campus buildings include the historic Old College buildings of Dundee Business School, the Bernard King Library, and others.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] The Bernard King Library in Bell Street opened to learners in February 1998 and was formally opened by Queen Elizabeth II on 30 June 1998.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] The library was voted best new building in Scotland in the 1998 Scottish Design Awards competition.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] The Abertay cyberQuarter opened in June 2022 with they key aim of bringing together students, academics, and organisations to help solve global cybersecurity challenges.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] The centre offers a physical space for collaboration and experimentation using digital tools and technologies.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] Abertay is a small university that receives the majority of its funding for teaching rather than research.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] Nevertheless, according to the results of the Research Excellence Framework 2014 (REF2014), Abertay was the highest ranked modern university in Scotland for 'research intensity'.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] The university submitted an increased proportion of staff in REF2014 compared to RAE2008 and achieved an average score of 2.15 – which in REF terms means "quality that is recognised internationally in terms of originality, significance, and rigour".
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] This was an improvement from the average score of 1.83, "national recognition", achieved in RAE2008.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] The Research Excellence Framework 2021 (REF2021) published on 12 May 2022 and Abertay recorded a 23% increase in research that is "internationally excellent" or "world-leading" since the last REF in 2014.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] In 2009 it established the UK's first Centre for Excellence in Computer Games Education, and a business support programme.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] Abertay runs five of the 25 interactive and games degree courses accredited in the UK by Creative Skillset, the industry skills body for the creative sector, more than any other institution.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] The university was established by a statutory instrument The University of Abertay Dundee (Scotland) Order of Council 1994.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] The order sets out the objects of the university and the general functions of the University Court to 'conduct the affairs of the university and carry out and promote its objects'.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] Abertay was the UK's first University to be recognised as a Centre for Excellence in Computer Games Education.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] The Centre for Excellence is accredited by Skillset and has strong links with industrial partners from across the broadcast, interactive and wider digital media sectors.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] These partners include BBC Scotland, BBC Vision, BSkyB, Channel 4, Electronic Arts, Codemasters, Blitz Games Studios, Rare, Sony Computer Entertainment Europe, Microsoft and Disney Interactive.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] Abertay was the first university in the world to have a degree in Ethical Hacking, differentiating from its other cyber-security degree counterparts by taking a more offensive approach to security.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] The university began to offer this degree in 2006.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] In 2020 the university was one of eight in the UK, and the only one in Scotland, to be named an Academic Centre of Excellence in Cybersecurity by the National Cybersecurity Centre.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] The university is also home to the Ethical Hacking society, which hosts the Securi-Tay conference, the largest student-run security conference in Europe.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] Abertay provides a range of short courses that provide the public with opportunities to improve current skills and enhance knowledge in several areas including digital marketing and sustainability.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] Fully funded by the Scottish Funding Council, the courses are free to applicants.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] Each short course is credit-bearing and a recognised university qualification.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] Prior to 1953 no coat of arms was registered in the name of the college.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] The original Ensigns Armorial were recorded in the Public Register of All Arms and Bearings in Scotland on 25 July 1953, in the name of Dundee Technical College.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] They were subsequently transferred to Dundee College of Technology in 1977, then to Dundee Institute of Technology in 1988 and, finally, to the University of Abertay Dundee on 25 April 1994.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] The top left sector is taken from the arms of Sir David Baxter of Kilmaron, who bequeathed a significant sum of money in order to establish the original Dundee Technical Institute in 1888.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] The top right sector is taken from the arms of Sir William Dalgleish, who was the senior trustee of what by then was known as Dundee Technical College and School of Art, and who opened the first building – Old College – on Abertay's present campus on Bell Street in 1911.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] The top middle sector of three chevrons is the heraldic symbol for "technical".
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] The pot of lilies in base is taken from the arms of the City of Dundee, with the books on either side representing education.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] Aaron McCauley, a graduate of Abertay, designed and registered the Abertay tartan in 2003.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] The tartan is based on Abertay's promotional colours of dark blue, red, gold and green from its coat of arms.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] The Abertay Students' Association (Abertay SA) is based in the ground floor of the Bernard King library building.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] Abertay SA co-ordinates all societies and acts as the voice and representation of all of Abertay's students.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] Abertay University has a wide group of sports teams competing under the university banner.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] It ranges from Tennis to Hockey who compete in the BUCS (British Universities & Colleges Sport) leagues, which competes against other universities and colleges in Scotland.
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] The Football, Hockey and Basketball teams have their 1st teams competing in the highest league (BUCS 1A).
[src:robert-gordon-university/abertay-university] The university has a fierce rivalry with Dundee University, competing in a yearly Varsity competition.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] Founded in 1872 as **University College Wales, Aberystwyth**, it became a founder member of the University of Wales in 1894, and changed its name to the **University College of Wales, Aberystwyth**.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] In the mid-1990s, the university again changed its name to become the **University of Wales, Aberystwyth**.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] On 1 September 2007, the University of Wales ceased to be a federal university and Aberystwyth University became independent again.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The annual income of the institution for 2024–2025 was £124.8 million of which £19.2 million was from research grants and contracts, with an expenditure of £130.3 million.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] In the middle of the 19th century, eminent Welsh people were advocating the establishment of a university in the principality of Wales.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] One of these, Thomas Nicholas, whose book, *Middle and High Class Schools, and University Education for Wales* (1863), is said to have "exerted great influence on educated Welshmen".
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] Funded through public and private subscriptions, and with five regional committees (London, Manchester, Liverpool, North and South Wales) guaranteeing funds for the first three years' running costs, the university opened in October 1872 with 26 students.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] Thomas Charles Edwards was the principal.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] In October 1875, chapels in Wales raised the next tranche of funds from over 70,000 contributors.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] Until 1893, when the college joined the University of Wales as a founder member, students applying to Aberystwyth sat the University of London's entrance exams.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] In 1885, a fire damaged what is now known as the Old College, Aberystwyth, and in 1897 the first 14 acres of what became the main Penglais campus were purchased.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] Incorporated by royal charter in 1893, the university installed Albert Edward, Prince of Wales, as chancellor in 1896, the same year it awarded an honorary degree to the former British prime minister, William Gladstone.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The university's coat of arms dates from the 1880s.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The shield features two red dragons to symbolise Wales, and an open book to symbolise learning.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The crest, an eagle or phoenix above a flaming tower, may signify the college's rebirth after the 1885 fire.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The motto is *Nid Byd, Byd Heb Wybodaeth* ('a world without knowledge is no world at all').
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] In the early 1900s, the university added courses that included law, applied mathematics, pure mathematics and botany.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The Department for International Politics, which Aberystwyth says is the oldest such department in the world, was founded in 1919.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] By 1977, the university's staff included eight Fellows of the Royal Society, such as Gwendolen Rees, the first Welsh woman to be elected an FRS.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The Department of Sports and Exercise Science was established in 2000.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] Joint honours psychology degrees were introduced in September 2007, and single honours psychology in 2009.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The chancellor of the university is Dame Nicola Davies, who took up the position in January 2025.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The visitor of the university is an appointment made by the privy council, under the royal charter of the university.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] Since July 2014, the holder of this office is Sir Roderick Evans.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] In 2011, the university appointed a new vice chancellor under whom the academic departments were restructured as larger subject-themed institutes.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] In 2022, the university celebrated its 150th anniversary, being established in 1872 (known at the time as The University College of Wales).
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The Institute of Biological, Environmental and Rural Sciences (IBERS) is a research and teaching centre which brings together staff from the Institutes of Rural Sciences and Biological Sciences and the Institute of Grassland and Environmental Research (IGER).
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] Around 360 research, teaching and support staff conduct basic, strategic and applied research in biology.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The institute is located in two areas; one at the main teaching Penglais campus and another rural research hub at the Gogerddan campus.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] In 1998, the Department of Economics (founded in 1912), the Department of Accounting and Finance (founded in 1979) and the Centre for Business Studies merged to create the School of Management and Business.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] In 2013, the School joined the Department of Information Studies and the Department of Law and Criminology at a new campus at Llanbadarn Fawr.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The school was shortlisted for "Business School of the Year" in the *Times Higher Education* Awards (2014).
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] In 2016, the institute, minus the Department of Information Studies, was renamed the Institute of Business and Law, the remaining departments being renamed Aberystwyth Business School and Aberystwyth Law School.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The Department of Computer Science (founded in 1970), conducts research in automated reasoning, computational biology, vision graphics and visualisation and intelligent robotics.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] AberMUD, the first popular internet-based MUD, was written in the department by then-student Alan Cox.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] Jan Pinkava, another graduate, won an Oscar for his short animated film *Geri's Game*.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The Department of Geography and Earth Sciences (IGES) was formed, in 1989, from the former Departments of Geography (established in 1918) and Geology.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] Bowen map library, containing 80,000 maps and 500 atlases.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The College of Librarianship Wales (CLW) was established at Llanbadarn Fawr in 1964, in response to a recommendation for the training of bilingual librarians that was made in the Bourdillon Report on *Standards of public library service in England* (HMSO, 1962).
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The college grew rapidly, developing close links to the Welsh speaking and professional communities, acquiring an international reputation and pioneering flexible and distance learning courses.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] It claimed to be Europe's largest institution for training librarians.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The independent college merged with the university in August 1989 and the department moved to the Penglais campus a quarter of a century later.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] Following the merger, the new department took over responsibility for existing offerings in archives administration and modern records management.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The Department of International Politics is the oldest of its kind in the world.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] It was founded, shortly after the First World War in 1919, with the stated purpose of furthering political understanding of the world in the hope of avoiding such conflicts in the future.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] This goal led to the creation of the Woodrow Wilson Chair of International Politics, with Wilson having played a significant role in its creation.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The department has over 700 students from 40 countries studying at undergraduate, masters and PhD levels.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] It achieved a 95% score for student satisfaction in the 2016 National Student Survey, placing it as the highest-ranking politics department in Wales and within the UK's top ten.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The department has hosted notable academic staff in the field including E.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] Carr, Leopold Kohr, Andrew Linklater, Ken Booth, Steve Smith, Michael Cox, Michael MccGwire, Jenny Edkins and Colin J.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The Department of Law and Criminology (founded in 1901) is housed in the Hugh Owen Building on the Penglais campus, and includes the *Centre for Welsh Legal Affairs*, a specialist research centre.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] All academic staff are engaged in research, and the *International Journal of Biosciences and the Law* and the *Cambrian Law Review* are edited in the department.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] In 2013, the department joined the Department of Information Studies and the School of Management and Business at a new campus at Llanbadarn Fawr, as part of a newly created Institute of Management, Law and Information Studies.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] In September 2018, the department moved back to the Hugh Owen Building, based in the Penglais campus, and its name changed from Aberystwyth Law School to the Department of Law and Criminology.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] Aberystwyth has taught modern languages since 1874.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] French, German, Italian and Spanish courses are taught at both beginners' and advanced levels, in a research-active academic environment.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] One of its research projects is the *Anglo-Norman Dictionary*, based in Aberystwyth since 2001 and available online since 2005.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] Physics was first taught at Aberystwyth as part of Natural Philosophy, Astronomy and Mathematics under N.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] Grimley, soon after the foundation of the University College.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] It became a department in 1877, under the leadership of F.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The department was located in the south wing of what is now the Old College, but later moved to the Physics Building on the Penglais Campus.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The first chair in Physics was offered to D.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] Before the First World War, much of the early research in the department was undertaken in Germany.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] Early research in the 1900s was concerned with electrical conductivity and quantum theory, later moving into thermal conductivity and acoustics.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] In 1931, the department hosted the Faraday Centenary Exhibition.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] Williams was appointed to the Chair of Physics in 1938 where he continued his research into sub-atomic particles using a cloud chamber.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] Following the Second World War, research was concerned with mechanical and nuclear physics, later moving into the fields of air density, experimental rocket launching equipment and radar.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] In 2007, Aberystwyth established psychology as a "Centre for Applied Psychology" within the Department of International Politics.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] By 2011, psychology had moved into its current premises in Penbryn 5 on the Penglais Campus.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The department has over 550 undergraduate students, with degrees accredited by the British Psychological Society and is home to an MSc in Behaviour Change.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The main campus of the university is situated on Penglais Hill, overlooking the town of Aberystwyth and Cardigan Bay, and comprises most of the university buildings, Arts Centre, Students' Union, and many of the student residences.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] Just below Penglais Campus is the National Library of Wales, one of Britain's five legal deposit libraries.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The landscaping of the Penglais Campus is historically significant and is listed at Grade II* on the Cadw/ICOMOS Register of Parks and Gardens of Special Historic Interest in Wales.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The Llanbadarn Centre is located approximately one mile to the east of the Penglais Campus, near Llanbadarn Fawr, overlooking the town and Cardigan Bay to the west, with the backdrop of the Cambrian Mountains to the east.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] Llanbadarn Centre hosted Aberystwyth Law School and Aberystwyth Business School, which together formed the Institute of Business and Law.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The Department of Information Studies is also based there.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] Additionally, the Llanbadarn Campus is the site of the Aberystwyth branch of Coleg Ceredigion (a further education college, and not part of the university).
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] At Gogerddan, on the outskirts of town is located the university's major centre for research in land based sciences and the main centre for the Institute of Biological, Environmental and Rural Science.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The School of Art is located between the Penglais Campus and the centre of Aberystwyth, in what was originally the Edward Davies Memorial Chemistry Laboratories.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] A listed building, the Edward Davies Building is one of the finest examples of architecture in Aberystwyth.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The site of the original university is the Old College, currently the subject of the "New Life for Old College" project which aims to transform it into an integrated centre of heritage, culture, learning and knowledge exchange.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The university opened an international campus in Mauritius in 2015 operating as *Aberystwyth University (Mauritian Branch Campus)* and registered with the Tertiary Education Commission of Mauritius, but closed it to new enrolments two years later due to low enrolment numbers.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] Less than 200 students enrolled with the Mauritius campus, which had the capacity for 2,000 students, before its 2018 closure and the university lost more than a million pounds as a result of the venture.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] Most of the student residences are on campus, with the rest in walking distance of the campus and Aberystwyth town centre.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] Accommodation ranges from "traditional" catered residences to en-suite self-catered accommodation, and from budget rooms to more luxurious studio apartments.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] All have wired access to the university's computer network and a support network of residential tutors.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] Disabled access rooms are available within the existing student village.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] Aberystwyth University is placed in the UK's top 40 universities in the main national rankings.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] It is ranked 38th for 132 UK university rankings in *The Times/Sunday Times Good University Guide* for 2023, and the first university to be given the prestigious award "University of the year for teaching quality" for two consecutive years, in 2018 and 2019.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The *Times Higher Education World University Rankings* placed it in the 301—350 group for 800 university rankings, compared with 351—400 the previous year, and the *QS World University Rankings* placed it at the 432nd position for 2019, compared with 481—490 of the previous year.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] In 2015, UK employers from "predominantly business, IT and engineering sectors" listed Aberystwyth equal 49th in their 62-place employability rankings for UK graduates, according to a *Times Higher Education* report.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] Aberystwyth University was rated in the top ten of UK higher education institutions for overall student satisfaction in the 2016 National Student Survey (NSS).
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] Aberystwyth University was shortlisted in four categories in the *Times Higher Education* Leadership and Management Awards (THELMAs) (2015).
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] Aberystwyth University has been awarded the Silver Award under the Corporate Health Standard (CHS), the quality mark for workplace health promotion run by Welsh Government.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The university has been awarded an Athena SWAN Charter Award, recognising commitment to advancing women's careers in science, technology, engineering, maths and medicine (STEMM) in higher education and research.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] In 2007, the university came under criticism for its record on sustainability, ranking 97th out of 106 UK higher education institutions in that year's Green League table.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] In 2012 the university was listed in the table's "Failed, no award" section, ranking equal 132nd out of 145.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] In 2013 it ranked equal 135th out of 143, and was listed again as "Failed, no award".
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] Following the university's initiatives to address sustainability, it received an EcoCampus Silver Phase award in October 2014.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] In October 2015, the university's Penglais Campus became the first university campus in Wales to achieve the Green Flag Award.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The Green Flag Award is a UK-wide partnership, delivered in Wales by Keep Wales Tidy with support from Natural Resources Wales, and is the mark of a high quality park or green space.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] In 2013, the University and College Union alleged bullying behaviour by Aberystwyth University managers, and said staff were fearful for their jobs.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The singer Peter Karrie resigned his honorary fellowship in protest, he said, at the apparent determination to "ruin one of the finest arts centres in the country", and because he was "unable to support any regime that can treat their staff in such a cruel and appalling manner".
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] In Autumn 2024, students protested the reduction of opening hours at Hugh Owen Library, a cost-cutting measure.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] Students argued that the university had continued to promote their 24/7 Library until recent open days, and that they were going back on promises which had attracted many students to the University.
[src:robert-gordon-university/aberystwyth-university] The University initially met with students to discuss options to restore the library's original opening hours, but later rejected further requests for meetings, and refused to negotiate any further.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] An **academic senate**, sometimes termed **faculty senate**, **academic board** or simply **senate**, is a governing body in some universities and colleges, typically with responsibility for academic matters and primarily drawing its membership from the academic staff of the institution.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] Models of university governance can be unitary (also called unicameral) or dual (also called bicameral).
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] Unicameral models may involve leadership by either an academic senate-type body or, more commonly, a lay-led board/council-type body.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] In this arrangement, a senate-type body may still exist but in an advisory role to the board-type body that has full responsibility for governance.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] Within the European Higher Education Area (EHEA), there are some countries where universities are governed exclusively by senates.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] Analysis of systems in EHEA countries by E.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] Estermann, published in 2018, found that universities in Ireland, Estonia, Latvia and Poland had unitary governance with a senate-type governing body.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] As of 2022, of university systems in Europe analysed for the European University Association (EUA) by the same authors and N.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] In some EHEA countries, senates either do not exist or, where they do, they are an advisory body with no real power.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] Additionally, the Netherlands has a dual government system with two boards rather than a board and a senate.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] The 2022 analysis includes Belgium (Wallonia-Brussels) and Turkey (neither of which was included in Pruvot and Esterman (2018)'s analysis) as having unitary governance models.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] Asymmetric dual governance models with both a board and a senate are found in the Czech Republic, Croatia, Finland, Hungary, Luxembourg and France.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] Boards tend to be dominant, with the senate having real but limited decision-making power.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] Traditional dual governance models, where the senate typically has responsibility for academic matters and the board for strategic planning and budgets, are found in Austria, North Rhine–Westphalia (Germany), Italy, Serbia, Slovakia and Slovenia.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] It is also common in the UK, where governance varies between institutions.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] The 2022 analysis is in agreement, classifying England as traditional dual, although Scotland (not included in 2018) is considered to be dual-asymmetric.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] It also adds Estonia and Latvia, following governance reforms, the Czech Republic, which is reclassified from dual-asymmetric, and Hesse (Germany), Cyprus and Lithuania that were not previously included.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] Senates in the US tend to be larger and to have more sub-committees than senates in England or Australia, while very small senates (few than 30 members) are most common in Australia (where they are typically termed academic boards).
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] US and Australian senates normally have elected chairs, while in England the senate is chaired by the vice-chancellor (the chief executive and chief academic officer of the university).
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] Australian senates are less likely to be statutory bodies than those in the US or England, with only 37% being established as governing boards in their own right in a bicameral system and the others instead being sub-committees of the university council in a unicameral governance system.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] In the US, just under half (48%) of senates are statutory bodies, while in England two thirds (67%) have this status.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] The low percentage of senates that are statutory bodies in Australia has been driven, at least in part, by state legislation imposing unicameral governance similar to that found in England's post-1992 universities on their institutions.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] This similarity extends to the relatively narrow scope of responsibilities of the senates in Australia and in England's post-1992 universities, which is reflected in Australian senates having fewer sub-committees than their counterparts in England or the US.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] Bicameral governance systems are common at publicly funded universities in Canada. and are required for accountability and the decision-making process.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] In bicameral governance systems there are two governing bodies, the Senate and the Board of Governors.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] The Senate typically has oversight over the academic mission, strategy, educational policy and programming.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] The Board of Governors contributes to the overall strategic direction and oversees financial and operational decisions.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] Academic governance in the UK is normally defined at the level of individual universities, in their constitutional documents, except for the ancient universities of Scotland (see § Scotland below).
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] Changes to these must normally be confirmed by the Privy Council before going into effect (see Universities in the United Kingdom § Governance).
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] In general, the constitutional documents define the existence of the senate (in universities that have a senate), but whether the powers of the senate are defined in the constitutional documents or left to ordinances passed by the governing body differs between institutions.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] This imposes the responsibility on the governing body (council, board of trustees, etc.) that: "The governing body receives and tests assurance that academic governance is adequate and effective through explicit protocols with the senate/academic board (or equivalent)".
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] With the exception of Oxford and Cambridge and the ancient Scottish universities, most pre-1992 universities follow a bicameral 'civic' model, with responsibilities split between a university council and an academic senate.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] However, some bodies denominated as senates, such as those at Bristol and the University of East Anglia, only hold delegated authority from their university's council rather than having authority in their own right under the university's constitutional documents.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] The oldest university senate in the UK is at the University of Cambridge (see University of Cambridge § Senate and the Regent House).
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] However, this is the assembly of all MA graduates, similar to convocation at Oxford and Durham (and formerly at London), rather than an academic body.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] The *senatus academicus* at Edinburgh emerged at the start of the 17th century as the senior body within the university itself (then governed by the town council), containing the principal and the regents.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] The senate at Glasgow, consisting of the rector, dean of faculties and the professors, also emerged in the early 17th century and was responsible for conferring degrees and other matters internal to the university.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] It operated alongside the 'faculty', a committee consisting of the principal and the holders of the thirteen oldest chairs, which had the management of the revenue and property of the university.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] Both of these were merged into the *senatus academicus* under the 1858 act.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] When St David's College, Lampeter, University College London, King's College London and Durham University were established in the 1820s and early 1830s, academics were not initially involved in their governance.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] However, the situation did not last, with the first academic senates in England being established in the 1830s.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] Complaints of poor teaching against the professor of anatomy at UCL in 1829 (only a year after its opening) led to him being sacked, causing splits in the council (appointed by the shareholders) and a loss of confidence in the warden on the part of the college's professors.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] The warden resigned in 1831 and his office was abolished, and in 1832 the senate was established to give the professors more autonomy, although under a lay chair.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] This became the professorial board in 1907, when UCL was merged into the University of London.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] It is now the academic board of UCL, and is an exception to the normal modern practice of the senate being a representative body (see below), including all professors as well as elected representatives of other academic and non-academic staff.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] Proposals to replace the academic board with a smaller senate were rejected in 2020.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] At Durham, the chapter of Durham Cathedral (the governors of the university under the 1832 act that established it) passed a "fundamental statute" in 1835, passing the normal running of the institution over to an academic senate and a convocation of the members of the university.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] The senate, consisting initially of the warden, the three professors, the two proctors, and a member of convocation nominated by the dean and chapter, ran the ordinary business of the university and proposed regulations that convocation could confirm our reject.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] However, the chapter, as governors of the university until 1909, retained the power to overrule the senate and convocation or to take independent action, which they did on four occasions in the 19th century.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] The former senate of the University of London, established by its charter in 1836, was the general governing body of the university, appointed by the government and without any academic staff representation – the university at that time being an examining board that did not have any academic staff.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] In the universities established in first half of the 20th century, senates were generally only given limited powers while there was little check on the powers of the council.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] An exception to this was Manchester, which (as Owen's College, in 1880) has been identified as the origin of the bicameral civic system.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] Here, the senate was given the right to be consulted on all legislation and to give opinions on any matter concerning the university.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] Leeds followed Manchester, while Durham's 1937 statutes went even further, constituting the senate as the supreme academic body and giving it the right to be consulted on financial matters that affected the university's educational policy.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] This was the first time the senate was defined as 'supreme' when it came to academic matters, which would become common in the 1960s.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] It also introduced the innovation that all professors were not *ex officio* members of senate but instead formed an electoral constituency that selected representatives on senate, in the same manner as the non-professorial staff.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] However, the polytechnics, incorporated as Higher Education Corporations, that became universities in 1992 had a unicameral structure with little academic representation on their board their academic board being merely advisory to the vice-chancellor and the board.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] Government reviews, particularly the Dearing Review in 1997, pushed older universities towards this more corporate style of management.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] The Committee of University Chairs' code of best practice also reinforced that councils should have ultimate responsibility, with little concept of shared governance.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] There has also been a rise in the power of the executive at universities, linked to the increase in the importance of the 'higher education market'.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] As a result, senates, which tend to be large bodies that meet infrequently, have lost power relative to councils and executives in the pre-1992 universities.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] However, there are large differences between institutions in this regard, with some senates still retaining a large amount of power.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] In Scotland, the *senatus academicus* is the supreme academic body of an ancient university, given legal authority by the Universities (Scotland) Acts.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] The *senatus* is responsible for authorising degree programmes, issuing degrees to graduands and honorary recipients, and for the discipline of students.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] At the University of Glasgow, the Clerk of Senate (whose office is equivalent to that of a vice-principal) and Secretary of Court are also *ex officio* members of the Senate.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] In the United States of America the academic senate, also known as the **faculty senate**, is a governing body for a university made up of members of the faculty of the university.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] It was estimated in the 1980s that 60 to 80 per cent of university and college campuses in the US had some form of senate, and it is generally considered to be the standard form by which faculty participate in university governance.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] Most large American research universities have an academic senate, although Harvard University is one of the most prominent exceptions.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] The academic senate normally creates university academic policy that applies to the university.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] While a majority of universities and colleges have some form of an academic senate, some claim that the organization has more of a ceremonial role.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] However some researchers have found a negative correlation between centralization of university administration and the presence of an academic senate indicating that an academic senate acts as an organizational force for the decentralization of a university in the area of academics.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] The academic senate meets periodically with a published agenda.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] Meetings normally use *Robert's Rules of Order*.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] The senate will have a set of committees, both standing committees and ad hoc or working committees, which are assigned particular areas of responsibility for policy formation.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] The officers of the academic senate may include the president of the university and the provost of the university.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] Other officers are academic senate members who are elected to officer posts by the members of the senate.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] Deans of colleges as well as department chairs may be *ex officio* members of the academic senate.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] Motions, recommendations, or actions that are generated by the academic senate through discussion and which are passed by the body are never final and will normally be referred to the president of the university for final approval.
[src:robert-gordon-university/academic-council] Depending on the authorizing legislation or statutes and types of recommendations being made, boards of trustees, boards of regents or the equivalent may have to authorize senate recommendations.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The university awards degrees in a wide range of disciplines from BA/BSc to PhD, primarily in professional, technical, health and artistic disciplines and those most applicable to business and industry.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] A number of traditional academic degree programmes are also offered, such as in the social sciences.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] In addition, the university's academic and research staff produce research in a number of areas.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Following numerous mergers between these establishments, it became Robert Gordon's Technical College in 1910, then following further developments became Robert Gordon's Institute of Technology in 1965 and began to conduct increasing amounts of research and provide degree-level education.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] It became a university in 1992, and now mostly offering day classes to full-time students.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Robert Gordon was a Scottish merchant, who had grown up in Aberdeen and graduated from Marischal College.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Following a successful career, he retired to Aberdeen around 1720 where he prepared plans for a Hospital similar to that founded in Edinburgh by George Heriot.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Robert Gordon's Hospital, now Robert Gordon's College was established in 1750, almost two decades after Gordon's death.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The Aberdeen Mechanic's Institution opened in 1824 providing evening classes in subjects such as physics, chemistry, mathematics, book-keeping, maritime navigation and art.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] By 1855 it was receiving government funding as the School of Science and Art, with a Technical School founded two years later.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Government education reforms in the 1870s saw the Hospital system fall out of favour and encouraged mergers with other educational establishments.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] As part of these reforms, the Aberdeen Mechanic's Institute and Technical School merged with Robert Gordon's Hospital in 1881.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The resulting institution was known as Robert Gordon's College.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] It provided an education for boys but as a day school only, and evening and later coeducational day classes for adults in science, technology, commerce and general subjects.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Art classes offered by the Mechanic's Institution were transferred to Gray's School of Art which opened in 1885.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] By the end of the 19th century, Robert Gordon's College was a major provider of technical education, receiving large government grants.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] However, even this was not sufficient to meet demand for technical education, and dedicated Technical Colleges were being set up in other Scottish cities.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] As a result, in 1910 adult education activities were split from the school and became **Robert Gordon's Technical College**.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Also merged into the new Technical College was the city's School of Domestic Economy which provided classes in domestic science.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The day school for boys continued as Robert Gordon's College, and the two institutions shared a campus, buildings and until 1981, a Board of Governors and administrative staff.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] During the 1920s, the first Ordinary and Higher Certificates and Diplomas were awarded, and by the 1930s Robert Gordon's Technical College was made up of Schools of Engineering, Chemistry, Maths & Physics, Pharmacy, Art (including architecture), Domestic Science, and Navigation.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Around this time the first students began to be prepared for external degree examinations – for the University of Aberdeen's BSc in engineering.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] A system of student governance also developed, with a Student Representative Council formed in 1931.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] In the closing years of World War II, candidates started to be prepared to sit exams for external degrees of the University of London, in subjects such as Chemistry and Engineering, but only via part-time and/or evening classes.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] After 1945, to aid with settling large numbers of returning soldiers into a career, the Government backed a Business Training Scheme which allowed the Technical College to introduce courses in Business Administration.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] In 1955, the Technical College received a large area of land.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The architect Tom Scott Sutherland, purchased Garthdee House in 1953 and subsequently donated it and the estate in 1955 for a new school of architecture.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] These classes had taken place at Gray's School of Art, but had been expanding in the 1940s and 1950s and much more space was needed.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Following completion of an extension to the house, the new Scott Sutherland School of Architecture opened in 1957.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] In 1966, Gray's School of Art also moved to a new building on this estate with its Schoolhill building being repurposed for administrative use.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] By 2013, all activities had transferred to Garthdee, with the addition of land immediately adjacent purchased from Aberdeen City Council in the 1990s.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The 1963 Robbins Report on the future of UK higher education recommended major expansion, which led to the renaming of the institution to **Robert Gordon's Institute of Technology** to suggest its increasing role in higher education rather than further education.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] As well as new "plate-glass" universities, reforms following the report created the polytechnics in England, Wales and Northern Ireland.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] It also created the Council for National Academic Awards (CNAA) to allow non-university institutions (like the polytechnics and Scottish central institutions) to run programmes that graduated students with CNAA degrees.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The institute's first CNAA degree programmes began in pharmacy in 1967, then in engineering, chemistry and physics in 1969, and expanded at undergraduate and postgraduate level to all disciplines.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Around this time, the government also began to transfer non-degree teaching (e.g. certificate courses in navigation) to local-authority colleges.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] During the 1960s, an academic committee structure was set up, headed from 1969 by an Academic Council.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] During the 1970s, these committees underwent expansion and reform to improve participation by academic staff in decision-making.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] For the first time, a faculty structure was introduced, with Faculties of Art & Architecture, Engineering, Arts, and Sciences, led by deans.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] A department dedicated to providing computer services to the institute was also established in 1974, and the first professorships were introduced in 1975.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] In 1981, the separation of the Board of Governors and administration staff from Robert Gordon's College was completed, although the school and Institute continued to share some buildings.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Beginning in the 1970s, the institute also began to provide consultancy and training for the North Sea oil industry, particularly in engineering and offshore safety and survival.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Following the reforms of the Further and Higher Education Act 1992, the institute was awarded university status as *The Robert Gordon University* on 9 June 1992.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The new university inherited numerous small campuses, and during the late 1990s and 2000s embarked on large building projects to consolidate teaching at its City Centre and Garthdee campuses, assisted by a large purchase of land at Garthdee from Aberdeen City Council in the mid-1990s.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] In the 1990s and 2000s student numbers also increased considerably, requiring new and larger facilities.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] A merger with the University of Aberdeen was discussed in 2002, but was rejected in favour of remaining separate but working in closer collaboration.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] By 2000, the university had consolidated to two campuses, at Garthdee and a city centre campus at Schoolhill and St.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] However, it had been planned since the early 1990s to eventually move all facilities to a single campus at Garthdee and additional land was purchased to enable buildings to be constructed to house academic departments which had been at the city centre campus.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The first phase was completed in summer 2013 with the opening of the Sir Ian Wood building (formally opened in July 2015).
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] As of August 2017, all academic and administrative departments are located at the Garthdee Campus, with the university retaining a space within the previous Administrative Building to host events and activities offering staff, students and alumni training and funding to develop business ideas.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] In March 2024, the university announced a voluntary severance plan which included reorganising subjects such as digital marketing, journalism and hospitality.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The vice-chancellor Steve Olivier stated that the downsizing was key to "maintain [the university's] long-term financial sustainability", citing lower numbers of foreign students and increased costs as budgetary challenges, with 130 employees ultimately departing.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] In November 2024, a further 135 redundancies were announced with the intention of moving some staff within the university.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] While Olivier called the redundancies a "last resort", Unison criticised the handling of the consultation, highlighting the perceived lack of transparency towards university staff and the consultation period covering Christmas and New Year.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Liam Kerr, one of the MSPs for the North East Scotland electoral region, described the move as "a hammer blow to the future of our young people, our workforce and employers".
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] In March 2025, the Educational Institute of Scotland voted for strike action in response to the redundancies, with its general secretary Andrea Bradley describing them as "alarming" and the cause of "a serious impact on learning and teaching across the university".
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Olivier called the strikes "disappointing", adding that the university had "done all that it can to mitigate against the potential of compulsory redundancies".
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The planned dates for industrial action were 15 April, 1 and 7 May, and 8-12 September.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] In 2010, RGU gained international attention for awarding an honorary degree to controversial American businessman and future United States President Donald Trump.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] This was featured in the 2012 documentary film *You've Been Trumped* which documented the progress of the construction of Trump's golf course near Aberdeen from the point of view of local residents.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] In the film Dr David Kennedy, former Principal of the university, is shown handing back his own honorary degree in protest at the university's action in awarding the degree to Trump.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] In December 2015, the university's then Principal, Professor Ferdinand von Prondzynski, announced he was reviewing the honorary degree and expressed his alarm at statements made by Donald Trump.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] On 9 December 2015, the honorary degree was revoked.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] RGU publicly stated: "In the course of the current US election campaign (2016), Mr Trump has made a number of statements that are wholly incompatible with the ethos and values of the university.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The university has therefore decided to revoke its award of the honorary degree".
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The revoking of Donald Trump's honorary doctorate came in excess of 4 years after the businessman accused the then-incumbent US President Barack Obama of illegitimacy on the basis of unsubstantiated accusations that Obama was born in Kenya and therefore not a US citizen.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The inquiry found that whilst the Principal failed to declare this link at the time of Gordon McConnell's appointment, it also expressed the view of the board that he did not deliberately conceal any information.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The finding led to a letter of resignation from another of the three Vice-Principals, Paul Hagan, who condemned RGU for failing to punish the pair, stating that this damaged the institution.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Hagan later withdrew his resignation in response to Prondzynski's departure.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] On 9 August 2018, von Prondzynski announced that he would voluntarily step down from his post on 31 August.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] In the same press release, RGU announced that Deputy Principal John Harper had already been appointed to succeed Prondzynski.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] RGU operates a single campus in Garthdee, Aberdeen.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] For much of its history it was a greenfield site, with parts used as the gardens and estate of the Victorian manor of Garthdee House, farmland, and open meadows.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The first university buildings were in use from the 1950s.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The Garthdee campus has seen more development in recent years, with new buildings constructed since the late 1990s.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The campus extends to 23 hectares (57 acres), although some of this is currently landscaped parkland, undeveloped, or under construction.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] In addition, the university owns a further 8 hectares (20 acres) of land to the west (primarily woodland) and 22 hectares (54 acres) at Waterside Farm on the opposite bank of the River Dee.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Until 2017 the university continued to operate one non-academic facility in the city-centre.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The building at Schoolhill is situated next to the Aberdeen Art Gallery and Robert Gordon's College, a private school which is no longer affiliated to the university but shares a common heritage and motto.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The Administration Building is a listed building, constructed from granite like many buildings in Aberdeen.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Also located there was the old city centre campus.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Many of these buildings were sold over the years to Robert Gordon's College for school use, while others have been sold for redevelopment.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Andrew Street building (which had been replaced by the Sir Ian Wood building at the Garthdee campus) was sold to the Canadian hotel Sandman Hotels group to be converted to a four-star hotel.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The 12,000 square metre building was constructed around 1908 and had served as the Aberdeen College of Education until purchased in 1968; the university claimed it to be the third-largest granite building in Europe, after the Spanish Escorial palace near Madrid, and Marischal College.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The former Administration Building is located on Schoolhill.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] It initially housed Gray's School of Art and was designed by the Aberdeen architect Alexander Marshall Mackenzie.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] As the school grew in size, the building was extended in 1896 and again between 1928 and 1931.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] However, it eventually became too small and when the school moved to a new building at Garthdee in the 1960s, the building was converted for administrative use.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] From then until 2013 it housed the Principal's office, which moved to Garthdee House at the Garthdee campus, followed by the administrative staff in 2017.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] In 2019, the Administration building was redeveloped with Robert Gordon University retaining part of the building to host events and activities.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Academic activities at the university are divided into 11 schools.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Each school is led by a head of school and is sub-divided into departments.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] There are also numerous administrative departments which support the university's activities.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] All academic Schools and Departments are based at the main Garthdee campus.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Under the terms of the Further and Higher Education (Scotland) Act 1992 and *The Robert Gordon University (Scotland) Order of Council 1993*, the university's governing body comprises a Board of Governors, consisting of 23 governors appointed to exercise the functions of management and control.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The official head of the university is the Chancellor, although in practice they act mainly in a ceremonial or symbolic role.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] At an operational level, most of the day-to-day management and control of the institution is delegated to the Principal and Vice Chancellor (commonly known simply as the Principal).
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The Board of Governors also delegates functions relating to the overall planning, co-ordination, development and supervision of academic affairs to the university's Academic Council.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Both the Board of Governors and the Academic Council are supported by a wide range of committees.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] At Scottish universities, the Principal of the university is its general chief executive and is the administrative head of the institution, second in precedence only to the Chancellor.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] This means that the day-to-day running and leadership of the university is the responsibility of the Principal.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] In the subject league tables from *The Guardian*, it was first in Scotland for four subjects in 2017 (Health Professions; Journalism; Architecture; and Pharmacy), while securing three subjects in the UK top 10.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The university is an active member of the University of the Arctic.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] UArctic is an international cooperative network based in the Circumpolar Arctic region, consisting of more than 200 universities, colleges, and other organizations with an interest in promoting education and research in the Arctic region.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The university also participates in UArctic's mobility program north2north.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The aim of that program is to enable students of member institutions to study in different parts of the North.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The university's logo and corporate identity make frequent use of the colour purple and the "Gordon" font, all of which appear extensively on campus signage, printed material and online.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The current logo was unveiled in February 2013.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] From 2009 to 2013, the logo consisted of a roundel derived from the university's coat of arms.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] However, current university branding typically leaves it out although it is still used for graduation.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The arms consist of a shield only and are used infrequently, usually at formal occasions such as graduation, and can also be seen over the main entrance to the university's Administration Building at Schoolhill and various academic buildings at the main campus at Garthdee.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The shield also formed the previous logo which still features on some older signage.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] On the left side of the arms, the three boars on a blue background edged in gold are taken from the arms of the Gordon family, while on the right the castle on a red background is taken from the arms of the City of Aberdeen.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] This symbol of the city is shared with the arms of the University of Aberdeen.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] A black wavy band divides the two sides, and features heraldic symbols in gold representing technology (a mechanical cog), learning (a flaming torch) and commerce (a gold coin).
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The university's motto is *Omni Nunc Arte Magistra*, which translates literally from Latin as "*Now by all your mastered arts...*", as if to suggest making use in everyday life of knowledge and skills gained.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] It is sometimes translated as "*Make the best of all your abilities*", although this is a somewhat more liberal rendering of the Latin.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] It comes from Virgil's *Aeneid*, Book VIII, line 441, as the god Vulcan encourages his workers at the forge.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] It shares this motto with Robert Gordon's College, who use it more frequently.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Unlike some universities, the motto is not seen frequently, although it has appeared in graduation materials and is engraved on the shaft of the university's ceremonial mace.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Like most Scottish universities, RGU has its own tartan; it mirrors the university's official colours of Royal Blue, Red and Gold which appear on the coat of arms (although the purple brand is now the recognised face of the university).
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The tartan was designed by Michael King in 1997.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Some students on their graduation day choose to wear a tartan kilt.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Academic dress is normally only worn at graduation ceremonies and occasionally at other very formal events.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] In common with most British universities, graduands begin the ceremony wearing the dress of the degree to which they are being admitted except for the hood.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] BA, BSc, etc.) and integrated Masters (e.g.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] MPharm, MEng etc.) a black gown is worn, ending 12 inches (30 cm) from the ground.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] For all other master's degrees except MPhil (e.g.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] MSc, MBA), a black gown is worn, ending 8 inches (20 cm) from the ground, while for MPhil the gown is the same but also has facings of white silk 2.5 inches (6.4 cm) in width.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] PhD), the Doctor's black robe (a black Panama gown) is worn; the Doctor's robe has front edges and sleeves in white silk.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The Chancellor's robe is of black silk with front edges and fringes of pale gold, while the Principal/Vice-Chancellor's gown is the same but with front edges and fringes in white.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] For higher doctorates (including honorary doctorate), the robe is scarlet with white front edges.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] All hoods are black and white and do not vary in colour by academic discipline, and all are of Cambridge shape.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The hood is only put on after the degree has been awarded.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] For all bachelor's degrees, the hood is black, partially lined with white silk embossed with symbols from the university's coat of arms (the castle, torch, and mechanical cog) and has a black square backpiece (known as the "cape").
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] For master's degrees, the hood is black and fully lined and edged in white silk embossed with the same symbols from the coat of arms, and the cape also edged in white silk 0.5 inches (1.3 cm) in width.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] For Doctoral degrees the hood is as for master's degrees but with a 1-inch (2.5 cm) band of white silk around the cape, while for higher doctorates and honorary doctorates the hood is scarlet and lined with white silk.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] For all bachelor's and master's degrees, headdress is a plain black mortarboard while for Doctoral degrees, headdress consists of a black Tudor bonnet with white cord and tassels.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Recipients of higher doctorates and honorary doctorates wear the same bonnet but with gold cord and tassels.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] In 2023/2024 there were 18,000 students studying on campus and online.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] As well as full-time and part-time on-campus study, the university provides a range of distance learning facilities over the internet via its virtual learning environment, CampusMoodle.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The first Student Representative Council was organised at Robert Gordon's Technical College in 1931, with activities such as sports clubs and societies following in the 1940s.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] A Student Union building opening in 1952 at Rubislaw Terrace in the city's West End.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] In 1969, the shop and bakery next to Gray's School of Art (now the ONE Tech Hub) on Schoolhill came on the market and were purchased by Robert Gordon's Institute of Technology.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The Student Union building opened there in 1974 and remained until its closure in July 2014 as the campus relocated to Garthdee.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] RGU:Union moved to Union Way by RGU Sport, and as of 2021 is now located within the Riverside Building.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] RGU:Union operates a student media program with RGU:Radio, RGU:TV and *Radar Magazine*.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The student radio station, called RGU:Radio broadcasts live from a studio on campus, running a number of shows from music to current affairs.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Broadcasts are streamed and regular podcasts are posted online.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] RGU:TV produces regular videos about campus events, topical issues and student life and distributed them online through a YouTube channel.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The university's Accommodation Services department arranges for students to be placed in one of nine halls of residence across the city.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] By far the largest of the halls of residence are the Woolmanhill Flats at St.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The Woolmanhill flats have over 700 one-person bedrooms, arranged in self-catering flats of up to eight.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The Woolmanhill Flats development was constructed in stages in the late 1980s and early 1990s by the university working in collaboration with a private developer.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The newest hall of residence is the Crathie Student Village on Holburn Street, and houses approximately 100 students.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Other halls of residence include two buildings on the Garthdee Campus; the Square Tower and the Round Tower.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] These distinctive pink buildings were constructed in the early 1990s and inspired by traditional Scottish tower houses.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] They have received architectural acclaim by critics and are included in *Prospect* magazine's list of the 100 best Scottish modern buildings.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] When the list was published in 2005, the Round and Square Towers were the only buildings in Aberdeen to be included.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] A number of other halls of residence across the city are used, some operated in-house by RGU and others by private companies.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Peter's Halls and Linksfield Halls which were constructed by the University of Aberdeen and then privatised in the early 2000s.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Students also have access to the private halls of residence in Aberdeen which are operated on a commercial basis by specialist companies, such as those owned and operated by the Unite Group.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] RGU SPORT at the Garthdee campus provides a wide range of sport and fitness facilities to the university community as well as to the general public.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Facilities include a 25m pool, various gyms with extensive facilities for cardiovascular training and resistance training (including free weights), a large sports hall (also used for exams), climbing wall, numerous fitness classes, physiotherapy, podiatry and sports massage.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Students can obtain a gym membership free of charge and staff and graduates of the university receive a discount on use of these facilities.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] There are over 32 campus sports clubs run by RGU:Union, and the university competes in Scottish Student Sport (SSS) and British Universities and Colleges Sport (BUCS) competitions.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] Swimmer Hannah Miley studied at RGU until 2013 and appeared in publicity for the university.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] A sport scholar program provides support for the athletic and academic careers of developing and elite athletes, including coaching, access to training facilities and financial assistance, as well as flexibility in fitting training around the academic timetable.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The Robert Gordon University Boat Club contests the annual Aberdeen Universities Boat Race each Spring against the University of Aberdeen.
[src:robert-gordon-university/robert-gordon-university] The two universities also compete annually in the Granite City Challenge which sees teams across a range of sports compete to be the best in the city.
